¡Animando en #Guayaquil! 🩵

Este fue el proceso: 

1. Grabé la calle 🎥
2. Me grabé como referencia
3.  Usé mi referencia para hacer un sketch rápido
4. El sketch me sirvió como guía para los cuadros finales ✍️
La animación fue creada en #RoughAnimator y la composición final fue hecha en #AfterEffects 😎

🍎 #ThinkEcuador

———-

Animating in Guayaquil! 🩵

This was the process:

1. I recorded the street 🎥
2. I recorded myself as a reference
3. I used my reference to make a quick sketch.
4. I used the sketch as a guide for the clean frames ✍️

The animation was created in #RoughAnimator and the final composition was made in #AfterEffects 😎.

Exciting news! Our short film “Dream To Cure Water” is a finalist at the prestigious @jacksonwildorg film festival in the “Climate Stories - Short Form” category.

We’re thrilled to unveil the trailer, showcasing two Peruvian mountain communities uniting ancestral traditions and cutting-edge science to combat climate change’s impact on their water source.

Watch the trailer on Vimeo (link in my profile) for the full experience.
#DreamToCureWater #JacksonWildSummit

Huge thanks to our dedicated team for their hard work and unwavering commitment. 
Special thanks also to @insidenatgeo and @theclimatepledge for all the support and funding the film.

My story about skiing in Caucasus Mountains in Georgia is live today on @natgeo! I am thrilled to finally share this series that I worked on last year. Traveling to Ushguli, which is protected by UNESCO, has been on my bucket list for a long time, and it’s one of those timeless places you can’t help but return to. Huge thanks to the amazing assistance of @shako_margiani and @maticek. Thanks also to great @natgeo team @rebekahbellbarlas and @maurafriedman. 

Please follow the link in my profile to read the story on @natgeo. I’ll be sharing more from this trip in the coming days, so stay tuned.
#natgeo #skitouring #georgia #svaneti #ushguli #leica #leicaSL

My story about skiing in Caucasus Mountains in Georgia is live today on @natgeo! I am thrilled to finally share this series that I worked on last year. Traveling to Ushguli, which is protected by UNESCO, has been on my bucket list for a long time, and it's one of those timeless places you can't help but return to. ‘What's the Correct Color of a Bee?’ made the @nytimes list of top dispatches in 2023 and WON 1st honorable mention in the outstanding features category at the SEJ’s awards for reporting on the environment! ✨ SEJ - The Society of Environmental Journalists is association of professional journalists dedicated to more and better coverage of environment-related issues. It was great to work on this story with the incredible writer @denisehruby. The photographs were captured in Austrian's state of Carinthia, where the law favors light-colored local bees. @nytimes @sejournalists @boshnaqmona @adamjdean @leica_akademie_austria #nytimes #award #beekeepers #leica

I was incredibly fortunate to discover the Mrežnica River in Croatia last year while working on the River Champions campaign for @nature_org . The Mrežnica River is a natural gem, and we were privileged to collaborate with some remarkable and passionate individuals who really care about river conservation in the Balkans. @toorkish_coffee Asim Ugljen, a well known Croatian actor, kayaker and a father who loves spending time on the Mrežnica River shared his story with us. Thank you, Asim, for your time and inspiration.

Thanks also to Krešo Rogoz @krogoz and @croatiaopenlandtoursfor logistic support and raft/kayak guidance. If you wish to explore the Mrežnica river do not hesitate to contact Krešo to help you discover the river. @croatiaopenlandtours

The Western Balkans region is home to some of Europe’s last free-flowing rivers. There is a growing movement of people who are fighting to protect these unique ecosystems for generations to come. We were given the task to produce 8 short films about river champions and guardians, from scientists to locals who are trying to protect rivers in the Balkans.

#riverchampions #thenatureconservancy #unitedforrivers #tentfilm

I am honored to serve as a nominator for the LOBA 2024 once again. The Leica Oskar Barnack Award is one of the most important photography awards, and I will never forget when I received this  recognition in 2013. We are actively seeking bodies of work centered around the theme of the relationship between humans and their environment.

If you believe you have a compelling and relevant series, please feel free to send me an email at ciril@tentfilm.com, including your work and an artistic statement. Additionally, you are welcome to tag someone whom you believe deserves this recognition. 

Attached are some photos from my LOBA-winning series 'Waiting to Move,' captured during my expedition to Shishmaref, Sarichef Island, Alaska. The purpose of this journey was to document the effects of climate change on the lives of the Iñupiat people.
@leica_camera @leica_camera_austria

@pazaramaco ile #işbirliği 

Bu yaz için bir tatil planı yaptınız mı?

Bodrum’da eşsiz denizin tadını çıkarmak ve Bodrum Kalesi’nde bulunan Sualtı Arkeoloji Müzesini ziyaret etmek ve akşam Gümüşlük’te harika yemekler eşliğinde gün batımını izlemek gibi ya da Marmaris’te Hisarönü Kız kumu plajında yüzmek ve Selimiye’nin harika manzarasında bir akşam yemeği yemek gibi.

Pazarama Tatil’le 1 Haziran – 30 Eylül tarihleri arasındaki tüm yurtiçi otel rezervasyonlarını Nisan ayında yaptığınızda anında 500 tl indirim kazanma şansınız var!

Ayrıca bu yaz yurtdışında Paris’in parklarında, bahçelerinde yazın keyfini çıkartmak ya da Barselona’da sahillerinin ve İspanyol yemeklerinin keyfine varmak ister misiniz? 

O zaman hemen Pazarama Tatil’e girin ve bu güzel yerler gibi birçok yurtdışı otel rezervasyonunuzu Nisan sonuna kadar %5 indirimli yapın. 
Detaylar pazaramatatil.com sitesinde.

@pazaramaco ile #işbirliği
Size şubat ayı sonuna kadar geçerli güzel bir haberim var!
Pazarama Tatil üyelerine özel 7.500 TL ve üzeri otel rezervasyonlarınızda  UYE300 kodu ile anında 300 TL indirim ! 

Ve yurt dışı seyahat planları olanlar için de yine çok güzel bir haberim var. 
Şubat ayı sonuna kadar Pazarama Tatil’den  yapacağın yurt dışı uçak bileti alımında , yurt dışı otel rezervasyonlarında geçerli %7 indirim  şansı yakala!
 
Detaylar 👉🏻 pazaramatatil.com sitesinde

The Ford GT90 Concept Car 

Unveiled in 1995 to celebrate Ford's 90th anniversary and honor the iconic GT40, the Ford GT90 concept car was a bold statement of automotive innovation. It housed a potent quad-turbocharged 6.0-liter V12 engine generating up to 720 horsepower. 

It included advanced features like carbon fiber construction, traction control, and active suspension, the GT90 boasted impressive performance figures, reportedly hitting a top speed of 253 mph (407 km/h) and achieving 0-60 mph in just 3.1 seconds. Despite its acclaim, the GT90 never saw production, serving as a testament to Ford's boundary-pushing engineering and design capabilities.

Rumor has it that only one GT90 Concept Car was ever made, and it currently resides at the Hajek Motorsports Museum in Ames, Oklahoma.

One of the most exciting shoots I did last year was working with the @eastafricanreptiles & Taylor Ashe Antivenom center in Watamu, Kenya to photograph spitting cobras. This particular snake is a Red Spitting Cobra (Naja pallida). Photographing these snakes is a challenge because they are not only highly venomous but they can be very aggressive/defensive as well. I had to wear a full face shield, which allowed me to avoid getting any of the venom they spit in my eyes, nose or ears.

Snakes are sadly often misunderstood and killed on sight no matter the circumstance, which is horrible because they are such a vital part of the eco systems we all live in. Organizations like East Africa Reptile's focus much of their attention not only on education and safety,  but in helping to safely remove snakes from people's homes and properties around Kenya, further increasing their chances of survival.

Sony a7R V w/ 90mm f/2.8 Macro Lens + 2 @godox_global V860 III OCF Units
#sonyambassador @sonyalpha #snakesofinstagram #snakesofig #snakesofinsta #snakestagram #dontkillsnakes

This is one of the most unique looking frogs you can find in Costa Rica, known as the Coronated Tree Frog. It's name comes from the fact that at certain angles, it looks as if it is wearing a crown. They can be found in the mountains around the area known as Sarapique, just north of San Jose. It is one of many different species of frogs and snakes that we look for during my Costa Rica wildlife workshops I run each January.

Be sure to swipe left to see this image in its full resolution!

Last September I found myself wandering around the deserts of Dubai in search of the Horned Arabian Viper. Unfortunately for me, it was the wrong time of year as they tend to love the hot desert nights. We did however find a number of these Saw Scaled Vipers (Echis Carinatus). These beautiful snakes are easily the most deadly snake in the UAE, accounting for more snake bites per year than all other snakes combined. They can be aggressive, have a quick strike and a very powerful venom.

Thanks to @wildlifewithnitin for showing me around! Can't wait for the next adventure!

Sony a1 w/ 90mm f/2.8 Macro Lens with two Good V860 III OCF units #sonyambassador #sonyalpha @sonyalpha

New series incoming! Embracing misfits from a solar eclipse, letting the moon’s craters distort the light as it bounces inside my lens. Help me name it in the comments - winner gets a print from the series!

UPDATE: Thanks for all the fantastic suggestions! “Luna Obscura”stuck out as a great way to describe how the lunar surface bends and scatters the light in the moments before totality, in effect acting as the first element in a lens 240,000 miles long. (you can see the crater shadows in the light beams when the video is paused) Congrats @danemachiela! Print heading your way!

Sunset through Yosemite fires, 2008. the quality of light through the smoke throughout the day was so surreal, it became a point of inspiration years later, when I used the color palette from this and another photo to create the Sierra filter on instagram.

Climbing brings us together.  Once you challenge yourself with gravity and share this experience with your friends something changes. It's the international language of belaying and spotting. It's the same everywhere. You have to trust someone to achieve your goals. 

@memphisroxclimbing has been a flywheel for the good that climbing brings. Built in the shell of a supermarket with a state of the facility, Rox is bringing gym climbing and outdoor experiences to South Memphis.

With a pay as one can model, the gym is open to everyone. Climbing as I was introduced to it was free. The cliffs were at  end of the road and my dad and his buddies had the gear and knowledge. I still recall the moment when climbing and being outdoors latched on. It's that same emotion that we see with the people we welcome to the crag, mountain and gym. Let's keep that going! 

The freedom that climbing brings comes at a cost. The facility and staff are monthly obligations. In business, as in climbing, the unexpected happens. In this case a burst water pipe needs immediate attention. To keep Rox a safe place (it's a polling station, health care facility and restaurant) the security team needs immediate funding. Going without costs the program more. 

Rox has been a part of my life for the past six years. I've made new friends, shared backcountry experience & knowledge while climbing outdoors and learned from each other on how to address the challenges of race in the United States. 

If you believe in the mission of @memphisroxclimbing please consider a donation. It will be put to good use. If you have the chance to visit Memphis, stop by the gym. You'll find family by the time you have warmed up.

#thankyou

The @khumbuclimbingcenter begins with a Puja ceremony. The students, instructors and volunteers hike to the lower Khumbila ice flows and share a meaningful start to the course. Aou Lama has been part of this tradition for 14 years. 
Once the ceremony concludes we toss toasted barley in the sky for long life. We then share the pemar (barley cake cone) and Losar biscuits. Once the goodness is lined out we begin climbing.

Kyle Allen Rott 1987 - 2023 
On  November  25th we lost Kyle in a fall in Hyalite Canyon, Montana. My heart goes out to his mother and sister and the South Dakota family of this fine man.  For his friends the loss is immediate. The years of being together,  weaving the fabric of friendship through shared experiences are gone.

Kyle was a climber. Once he realized that the pursuit of gravity was his life's calling,  he lived with a singular purpose. "Let's go climb."

As someone close to Kyle, his "uncle" by age and knowing him with our family, his loss is another weight on the scale of "is it worth it".

Many of my close friends are introverts. In school we found each other and climbing self selected us. Kyle and I climbed together for 15 years - most of the time hiking the folds of Southwest Montana looking for the cliffs and drips that sustain us. In between climbs he helped out by housesitting for the climbing community. For those of that trusted Kyle without houses and animals - you know how conscientious he was.  Kyle's humble approach to life - not entertaining anything superfluous - was reflected by living in his truck.  Which made housesitting a good balance. 

While Kyle was quiet and shy in a room of his peers, there was this friendly side that Kyle shared with people in life. More than once he would carefully explain the gadgets needed to climb to curious people on the trail. This translated well to the guiding he did with Montana Alpine Guides and the Mountain School in Yosemite. 

At our service for Kyle we wrote in a small book for his mother and family. His worldly possessions, kept tidy in a Livingston storage locker, spread out over a picnic table, passed to his friends. They will cherish his memory and then ply the seas of gravity, risking it all for the moment. For his age peers, dealing with non sequential death, many for the first time, left adrift questioning and bonding closer with those that stand. I was there. And now 30 years later as an elder, with culpability and responsibility.

We love you Kyle for energy you brought to our climbing adventures. 

We love you for the reminder to live calm. 

Photos @petetapley

The curb weight of the Porsche 356, the first Porsche automobile, was 1700 – 2,296 lbs. The weight of the Porsche name is much heavier. Ferdinand ‘Ferdi’ Porsche, an architect by trade and the great grandson of the company’s founder Prof. Ferdinand Porsche, is now adding his fingerprint to the family’s rich motor-sports legacy.

At 30 yrs old, Ferdi defies all the seriousness and pomp of racing cars. He’s affable, warm, and almost boyish in his excitement. To put it bluntly, he’s ‘cool’ without effort, working hard to invite the next generation into the motorsports world.

 On February 24, Ferdi’s F.A.T. International held its first ice race in Zell am See, Austria, and has followed it up in Aspen, Colorado. Over the past two days on an icy track in Carbondale, the race has included models from the @aetherapparel Half11 (half Porsche, half F1) to the Rivian R1T, to a host of various Mobil 1 cars tearing around corners, over-steering, under-steering, and generally bringing joy as they spit rooster tails of snow from their tires. 

I watch as an enthusiast warm his hands in the exhaust of a loud engine. He brings them to his nose, closes his eyes and inhales deeply, letting his senses coalesce into something whole and visceral. Ferdi sits in his car nearby grinning. It’s an expression of sincere, palpable joy. As an arm drops, he accelerates onto the track. In a burst of exhaust, something old becomes new again. It’s a Herculean task and these are enormous shoes to fill, but Ferdi seems to be carrying the weight of legacy effortlessly.

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // In the wide desert of Upper Mustang, the road planes along canyon walls and dry mountainsides dotted with hundreds of unspeakably ancient human-made caves. The light plays a slow game of chase with the shadows cast by the highest mountains on the planet, now behind us. We sweep the corners wide, drawn to cliff-edges teetering above the braided Kali Gandaki River below. We don’t know where to look – the road, the layers of tortured mountains, or the sand-castle parapets of rock and mud towering above us.
 
Instead, we watch the oncoming frame-bent jeeps as they roaring around the blind corners on bald tires. In Tsarang, the drivers share a rough kindness with us. We play snooker, a game we don’t know. Cory tries and fails to find a tutorial on YouTube. Nursing warm cans of beer, we realize the drivers don’t know how to play either.
 
The evening passes in one long, impossible game of scratches and flubs until the young man running the hall flicks the light switch and kicks us out into the cold, thin air of a star-streaked night.  @vacheronconstantin

Our hearts remain with the thousands of families that have lost loved ones in the 6.4 magnitude earthquake in West Nepal. As winter approaches, tens of thousands remain without adequate shelter or warmth. If you’d like to contribute please visit Blinknow.org - these are friends of ours working tirelessly on the ground, and every contribution matters.

We will resume our Mustang travelogue starting today to celebrate all the beauty, resiliency, and magic of Nepal in the faith that if we all work together, brighter days will come soon. // following words by @jetbutterflies Hoping for mountains, we find fog. Climbing towards Sarangkot, the city disappears behind us. Marigolds line the road that falls away into steeped terraces dotted by clusters of roughhewn homes. An hour in, we find the main highway again, paved and twisted into tight curls across the steep hillsides like a pig’s tail. Todd’s back wheel blows up, death-wobbling him across the narrow road and directly into a stable of split-open motor scooters under a corrugated tin roof held together with wire.

The mechanic opens the rear tire, and leaves the parts strewn across the shoulder of the highway. A metal-handled hammer and broken screwdriver finish the job: a blown bearing. The mechanic isn’t much of a talker. He saddles a scooter and buzzes off to somewhere while the town gathers around us, sharing stories and children and a, most proudly, new iPhone 12 ProMax.  They return with two bearings – “Japan” brand. “Best quality”, he says.
Four hours of riding to go. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

The thing about earthquakes is that they impact poor and vulnerable communities the most. Those who can’t afford to reinforce their homes, or who don’t have a surplus of resources like family, income, or grain to weather months of rebuilding and trauma.

In light of the recent 6.4 magnitude earthquake that struck Western Nepal last night - just miles from Mustang - and our hope to focus public attention on supporting relief efforts, we will postpone our travelogue until next week.

Currently, there are 150+ known deaths from the quake with many hundreds more injured and tens of thousands left without shelter as winter approaches. Please watch this space for updates on how you can help the families in Jajarkot and Rukum recover and build back better.

With love, 
Cory and Ben

MAD MAX
 
Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // The highway is a perpetual a fever dream of construction and destruction. Dust, scattered pavement, clawed ridges of clay are punctuated with the idle carcasses of heavy equipment, thin herds of goats, and garish tractors bouncing between knee-deep ruts. When you don’t have any lanes, you’re always splitting lanes.
 
Six days ago, Cory did what any responsible motorcyclist would do: he watched a YouTube video titled “How to Ride a Motorcycle in ONLY 1 HOUR,” which, it turns out, was only twenty minutes long. 
 
Cory then traced the backstreets of Santa Monica on a tiny café racer for five days before boarding a plane for Kathmandu. Now, eight hours of riding on Nepal’s worst and busiest highway later, the sun collapses across rice paddies heavy with grain. We still have hours to go.
 
In this perpetual present, when you’re gripped, you experience the relativity of time. It slows to a game of seconds until, as if by magic, hours have passed.

I’ve known Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies for over a decade. He’s a Kathmandu staple and has called Nepal home for twenty some years. He came for the mountains and stayed for the people, starting and running non-profits for pieces of the community. At his heart, he’s an artist and filmmaker. He’s also a ferocious writer. I’ve been to Mustang with him before on assignment for NG. But this trip is just for us. The following posts are his words.
 
Our other companion is Todd Hoffman. He doesn’t use Instagram. He’s one of those leather-faced legends of the eighties who lived hard and fast enough to know when to leave the racetrack. Even if you hardly know him, you want him on your team. At your back. If he looks familiar, it might be from that one time he took Pepsi to task over a Harrier jump jet.
 
The following posts are from our motorcycle trip from Kathmandu to Lo Manthang. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

More views from Vienna, this time from October 2023 on the new Phoenix color film.

The last few years have been (mostly) good for analog photography: the new Leica M6, increased use of ECN-2 film stocks and processing, news of a new line of Pentax film cameras — while we’re also facing rising film prices and ongoing economic issues elsewhere, I’ll take positive news when it comes.

When Phoenix was released, there was a certain amount of negativity about who was sent sample rolls as the launch coverage and reviews rolled out. The common complaint was that it was only sent to “influencers” — not a term I love, though people with influence have always been a good strategy for getting the word out.

The implication was that if Phoenix had been sent to “real” photographers for testing, the images would have been better, or the reviews wouldn’t have been as favorable, etc. — and that the generally-positive public feedback on the new film was only due to said influencers not wanting to get on Harman’s bad side.

This sort of commentary smells like jealousy, and I get it — there are a LOT of amazing photographers out there who haven’t been blessed by social media’s algorithmic deities, and it can be frustrating to see opportunities being handed to other people when you feel you could do better. However, indignance doesn’t do anyone any favors.

It’s also easy to be jaded, and say companies like @harmanphoto are making a money-grab by selling a limited edition product — though I’d wager most of the folks who made that argument happily took advantage of Black Friday deals.

Harman launched a new, niche product, and you can’t do that without promotion — if you can get the bulk of your press by sending people free product, more power to you.

So, let people be excited about new film! The world has enough darkness right now — choose to shine a light where you can.

(Continued in comments)

Heading back to Vienna next week — one of my favorite cities — to run another mini-workshop and photowalk with my buddy Jahan (@doyoudevelop) and the good folks at @leica_akademie_austria & @leica_camera_austria. Link in my bio + Stories, et al.

This time we’re digging into high-speed B&W film (3200ISO, pushing film, and the like), so I thought I’d share some images I’ve been sitting on for a while.

In February 2020, I was in Vienna for a few weeks and brought along a camera I’d had in my collection for years but never used: a Kodak Retina 1a from 1953.

I slowly captured a single roll of HP5+ while wandering Vienna’s streets, zone focusing at f11–16, pushing the roll 1-stop (effectively turning 400ISO film into 800ISO) to keep the shutter speeds higher at those smaller apertures.

I’ll share some more from this roll in a few days — it’ll be nice to revisit Vienna on high-speed B&W film nearly 4 years on 🎞️

Вот она - сила коллективного разума 🙌🏻👍🏻Благодаря вашим советам под вчерашним постом, квест по поиску зеленого яйца удачно пройден, скоро покажу сколько красивых оттенков у меня получилось 😍
А пока вспомним про тот самый бездрожжевой творожный кулич❤️🔥, который многие из вас так полюбили и каждый раз присылают мне благодарные отзывы! Спасибо всем большое! 🙏🏻❤️
Конечно мои отношения с некоторыми продуктами питания слегка поменялись с того момента🧐 А так как многие из вас интересуются, что будет если в оригинальном рецепте заменить белую муку на какую-либо другую или уменьшить количество сахара, я решила немного поэкспериментировать.
Что я рекомендую не исключать - это специи, они дают понятную вкусовую базу. Поэтому не пренебрегаем цедрой, ванилью, кардамоном и корицей (если, конечно, нет явных негативных восприятий от этих ароматов). Начинка любая вписывается отлично, на мой взгляд 👍🏻В этот раз я добавила сушеную вишню и ежевику. Количество сахара, уменьшенное в два раза, не повлияет на текстуру кулича. Сладость останется вполне ощутимой. Замена муки, безусловно, повлияет на вкусовые качества и на «лёгкость» кулича. В этот раз я использовала смесь овсяной муки ( она дает яркий ореховый вкусовой оттенок), муки из зеленой гречки и бурого риса. ВНИМАНИЕ⚠️ в карусели в рецепте не указаны 50 гр муки из зелёной гречки и 50 гр муки из бурого риса!!! Кулич получился в меру влажный, плотный, но достаточно мягкий. Результатом я довольна. 
В карусели будет оригинальный рецепт, а также моя зожная вариация )) Экспериментируйте!
I wish you all a very happy Easter! ❤️💐

Quem gosta de uma proposta mais escura? 
Projeto @depaulaenobrega

Compartilhar o nosso dia a dia dentro e fora do escritório é uma atividade que já faz parte da nossa rotina no IG do De Paula e Nóbrega e nós adoramos a forma como ela nos aproxima ainda mais de vocês. 🖤

Dentre os temas que mais recebemos perguntas, o de Gestão de Escritório é bastante recorrente. 

Pensando nisso, nós preparamos um série de Aulões Semanais Gratuitos, O Gestão DP&N, onde, nas próximas 04 semanas, iremos compartilhar com vocês alguns dos nossos métodos de trabalho, bem como dicas e sugestões de postura comportamental. Além disso, durante as aulas iremos também responder todas as dúvidas que forem surgindo.

E para melhorar ainda mais essa experiência, nós criamos um grupo no WhatsApp onde os participantes irão receber avisos e materiais de apoio sobre gestão. Para participar do grupo, basta enviar o seu contato via direct! 📲

Ontem, 13/10, nós realizamos o primeiro aulão com o tema Brienfing.

Se você perdeu, confira no feed do @depaulaenobrega tudo que aconteceu nessa nossa primeira conversa descontraída e bastante produtiva. 💡

⚠️ Mas corra, ela só fica disponível por 24h. 

E não esqueça, toda terça-feira às 17h15min aqui no nosso instagram, venha terminar o seu dia da melhor forma: aprendendo e compartilhando conhecimento.

Ukraine, February 2024

“Hi Anna. Our brigade surrenders in captivity today. Me too. I don’t know what will happen next. I love you all.”
_____________

Waiting for Serhiy

His attempts to escape the Russian siege had failed. He and his fellow Ukrainian Marines were surrounded, dozens of miles from friendly lines. They were nearly out of food and ammunition. Some panicked, others quietly resigned themselves to what would come next.
Then, a few days later, senior sailor Sergey Hrebinyk and his comrades emerged from the sprawling Ilyich Iron and Steel works in the southern Ukrainian city of Mariupol. He quickly messaged his older sister: “Hi Anna. Our brigade surrenders. In captivity today. I also don’t know what will happen next. I love you.”
It was April 12, 2022.

Nearly two years later, on the second anniversary of the start of Russia’s full scale invasion, Serhiy Hrebinyk, 24, remains in captivity as a prisoner of war, held somewhere in Russia. His family sits in purgatory, trapped between that day in April and the present.

The initial panicked flurry of calls to the Red Cross, the Ukrainian military and local officials subsided as official proof of life took months to come. The war dragged on, and now, like thousands of other Ukrainian families with relatives in captivity, the Hrebinyks wait.

“Life, of course, has changed. Almost every day is filled with tears,” said Svitlana Hrebinyk, Serhiy’s mother.

Words @tmgneff Photos @dguttenfelder Editing @adamjdean for @nytimes in Sumy. Ukraine marking two years of war since the full-scale Russian invasion.

Ukrainian soldiers rested inside a destroyed building on the edge of the newly liberated but desolate village of Blahodatne. It was one of seven villages that Ukraine had retaken during the early days of the counteroffensive against Russia and just one of dozens, or hundreds that would need to be bled over if their strategy could succeed. 

This photograph is part of the @nytimes 2023 The Year In Pictures. It’s been a year of very dark days and unprecedented danger for fellow journalists in Gaza and Lebanon, Israel, Ukraine... 

Please have a look at the pictures (link in my bio) and read the words of some of the women and men who stood their ground with their cameras.

Ukrainian military manning tanks and mobile artillery (and a “Buhanka”) on the Kharkiv front lines.

Ukraine October 2023

Emerging from an underground bunker in a tree line, Ukrainian soldiers fired their 50+ year old Soviet-era artillery at Russian frontline infantry near Bakhmut. 

The town cleared another acre of ground and began digging fresh graves to make room for many of the 52 killed in one vicious Russian missile strike on mourners who’d gathered for a wake in the village of Hroza. 

A steady flow of injured soldiers, cared for by combat medics in this hidden Donetsk region outpost. 

Boots and bloody clothing, cut away from injured Ukrainian soldiers before evacuation from the front, were heaped in the hallway and yard at one combat medic outpost in the Kupiansk direction. 

@nytimes

Yuri, a Ukrainian villager from Hroza, wandered in the ruins. His wife Halyna died here the day before. 

A missile strike on the Ukrainian village of Hroza killed at least 52 people, including every known member of one family in the area. As much as a third of the population were killed in the attack. 

“Everybody died,” one resident said.

@VGnett made a video reportage of my favourite hike in Norway. Link in bio!

Within a week I’ll begin my second bicycle-tour of Norway, but first I took my family to one of my favourite hikes in our county. Even my sister’s little dog joined us for the gruelling 21km hike with an elevation gain exceeding 1300m. At the summit someone had left homemade cloudberry liqueur. To whom ever made the liqueur it was delicious!

An empty Pulpit in June is impressive, but nothing compared to the 19-year-old adventurous Dutchie we met on the rock @guus_malenstein. His original plan was to cycle from the Netherlands to Trondheim (Norway), but the moment he arrived in Denmark his bike disintegrated. Without sufficient funds to make the repairs he decided to walk instead. At the Norwegain border he told the border guards that he needed to visit his grandmother. The guards let him in.⁣
⁣
I must admit, I’m impressed by the young crazy Dutchie. You don’t meet brave people like him daily, who are on a thousand-kilometre trek alone admits a pandemic. ⁣
⁣
🎥 @andreassolbakken

The moment my sister and I left for Rio de Janeiro the first case of covid-19 was confirmed in Norway. A week after arriving back home the entire world had shut down, I cannot believe our luck! I hope everyone is keeping strong during these unprecedented times. ⁣

I am really excited to announce my partnership with @biodermausa for 2024! You may remember that they were kind enough to donate $500k of skincare products to my healthcare colleagues during the pandemic and they loved them. One of the leading brands in dermatological skincare, BIODERMA is devoted to supporting medical professionals and consumers alike.

Since then, I have been a fan of many of their products, and now I’m excited to highlight them. Starting off this dry, irritating winter season is their Atoderm Shower Oil & Atoderm Intensive Balm.

Because my skin gets really flaky and itchy during the dry winter months, I’ve been using The Atoderm Shower Oil as a cleanser to help restore optimal hydration right from the shower. Then, post-shower, I follow up with The Atoderm Intensive Balm to lock in moisture to reduce dryness and irritation for the rest of the day. #biodermapartner #strongetogether

Bullfight, Isle Royale National Park. 
•
I caught these two young bull moose going head to head on one of the camera traps we had set up in @isleroyalenps.  This pretty much sums up the new techniques I’ve been using in my camera traps lately. Autofocus 😬. No lights 😳. Silent cameras 😎. It’s pretty tough going, but when it works, man it works.  I also think it’s a lot more likely to generate images capturing better behavior as there are no sounds or lights to disturb the animals while they’re doing their thing. What do you think?
•

ด้วยความรักในอาหาร (อร่อย) และอยากบอกต่อ @eatandshout จึงเกิดขึ้นเมื่อปี 2012 โดยเป็นที่รู้จักกันในกลุ่มเพื่อนเล็กๆ แล้วก็เริ่มมีคนรู้จักและติดตามมากขึ้นเรื่อยๆ จึงกลายเป็นแรงผลักดันในการค้นหาอาหารอร่อยจากทั่วโลกมาแบ่งปัน จนเมื่อสัปดาห์ก่อน Eat & Shout ได้ก้าวมาไกลอีกขั้น เมื่อได้รับรางวัล 🏆 Top Food Influencer จากเวที Influence Asia 2015 @influenceasia เราดีใจและภูมิใจมาก ที่มีคนเห็นความตั้งใจของเรา ☺️
🍴 Eat & Shout จะไม่มีทางก้าวมาได้ไกลขนาดนี้หากปราศจากครอบครัว เพื่อนๆ ที่มักชวนกันไปชิมอาหารอร่อยๆเสมอ รวมถึงร้านอาหารต่างๆ ที่เชิญไปรีวิว เปิดโลกให้เรารู้จักกับอาหารที่หลากหลายมากขึ้น ที่สำคัญที่สุดคือ Follower ทุกท่านที่ให้การสนับสนุน รวมถึงตามเราไปชิม ขอบคุณทุกท่านจากใจจริงค่ะ 😍 และที่ลืมไม่ได้คือเพื่อนร่วมอุดมการณ์พี่ @itan และ @ppgallery สำหรับกำลังใจ คำแนะนำต่างๆ และภาพสวยๆ จากในงาน ขอบคุณมากค่ะ 😊🙏❤️

Which Chef put together the more delicious looking Super Bowl Wings Inspired Spread? Team Drums led by Chef @monwahbs or Team Flats led by Chef @howardseivright ?

We all know that no event celebrates the spirit of competition like the Super Bowl. And we all know that food is a major part of that event. 

But did you know that there is a an even fiercer competition that has been going on between food lovers even before the first Super Bowl was played?

This battle is the battle for wing supremacy. Drums or Flats. The debate over which is the better bite is more intense than any football fans love for their favorite team and their despising of their rivals. 

So I got some @pintysfoods wings and two of my favourite chefs to battle it out by making the most appetizing Super Bowl spreads possible. 

We had a drafts, wing related trivia, and a lot of food and a lot of fun. Check it out!!!

In addition to my previous post with photos I just had to share a reel to show you all the details of the most wonderful stay at @cowleymanor which is now my favourite design hotel in the Cotswolds @experimentalgroup [press stay].

#visitcotswolds #hoteldesign #visitengland #iamatraveler #tlpicks

The hotel in the Cotswolds that has it all: incredibly beautiful design, delicious food, a spa with an outdoor and indoor swimming pool, a cocktail bar, a games room and friendly service - let me introduce you to @cowleymanor [press stay]. My first experience of @experimentalgroup hotels and hopefully not the last! We opted for lunch instead of dinner and enjoyed an excellent Sunday roast. Taking inspiration from each chapter of Cowley Manor’s book, spanning from 1695 until today, designer Dorothée Meilichzon has carefully woven together classical inspiration with contemporary elements - from baldaquin beds to bold colour patterns and use of rattan - I loved all the details! Scroll through to see a selection of photos I took, it wasn’t easy to choose just 10! A reel of our stay coming next😊

#visitcotswolds #visitengland #hoteldesign #tlpicks #iamatraveler #cowleymanor

I used a recent opportunity to take some photos inside Westminster Abbey, and while it’s a very popular tourist destination I managed to get a couple of shots when it wasn’t too crowded. 
Since 1066, it has been the location of the coronations of 40 English and British monarchs, and at least 16 royal weddings have taken place at the abbey since 1100.

#visitlondon #tlpicks #iamatraveler #prettycitylondon #thisislondon

Starting from today if you’re visiting Westminster Abbey, you can also explore the story of the French gothic masterpiece, Notre Dame de Paris from its earliest origins in the 12th century and its 850-year history to its restoration following the devastating fire of 2019 in this immersive, interactive exhibition. Open until the 1st June at Capter House @westminsterabbeylondon, the exhibition is included in the Westminster Abbey admission price but you need to book a time slot. 

#visitlondon #prettycitylondon #tlpicks #iamatraveler #thisislondon

“Light Walker”

A self portrait series from just a few weeks ago in Deadvlei, Namibia.  A place I’ve dreamed of visiting for a decade… and yet being there in person, walking barefoot across the dead marsh under these 600-900 year old skeleton trees, was such a surreal experience unlike what I imagined it would be.  It’s strange to walk through a place that feels so long dead and forgotten - yet still full of life and wonder.

I originally had an entirely different series of images in my mind for here, involving a couple of different colourful dresses (red and gold) and dance poses mimicking and flowing with these trees… but when I arrived here, just as the sun rose and lit up my surroundings and as I walked over the last sand dune to see the dead pan valley floor below, all those earlier visions I had simply vanished. Thankfully, tucked away in the bottom of my backpack under my camera gear and red/gold dresses (anyone else cram dresses and chocolate into their backpack as a general hiking norm?), I had also this white dress as a back-up… and I was so glad I brought it, because all I could actually envision in person here was a balance of death and life, light and dark, a dream walking through decay. 

And so that’s how I spent the next 3 hours - walking and running around barefoot, feeling connection, contrast and awe, and creating this new series as it came to me. 🤍 What a surreal place.

———

P.S. For those wondering, this dress was made by the lovely @kayame.wear 🥰

P.P.S  I plan on releasing an editing walk-through for one of these images to my newsletter subscribers in January. If you’re interested, sign up to my newsletter through the link in my profile! 🥰

“Heart of the Solstice”

21/100 of my current self portrait project. 💚

Wishing you all a beautiful winter solstice today (at least, winter to everyone up here in the northern hemisphere!)

I have to admit that I absolutely, undoubtedly LOVE these long, dark and moody days (sorry to all my summer lovers out there!)… and I sorta secretly long for winter solstice all year. 😅 

It’s a time where I somehow feel far less guilty about letting my mind and life slow down, where I can become like the trees and the bears in winter, resting quietly and hibernating from the world in my own little introverted cocoon.  It’s in the soft, quiet, candle-lit hours that I feel the most rested and at peace, and therefore more renewed and rekindled with creativity and short bursts of adventurous energy during the day - when these short hours of daylight are a gift, appreciated even more in the winter. 🥰

Anyone else feel the same way? 🕯️

In March of this year I got an email from an interior designer inviting me to work on a piece for an iconic resort at the Oregon coast. After months of designing, logistics, and then scheduling, we are here for 3 days working on this piece that will live on the property along side master art works from the past 60 years.

My announcement last week about stepping away from @modernmacrame has created an incredible response and a widening of possibilities. And being in the physical process is so refreshing.

I’m listening to an incredible book, #ninasimonesgum by @thewarrenellis and breathing in the crisp salt air.
I’ll share the finished piece when it’s done.
Cord by @modernmacrame 

Thank you @elkcollective 💫

For those asking, the play suit is by @dressedinlala

How often do you stop to measure your successes? I find it is usually easier to remember the difficult times, but in this moment, I would like to honor all that we have accomplished.

In the past 10 years since starting Modern Macramé, I have traveled the world teaching plant and wall-hanging workshops. I always dreamed of traveling for work, and I was lucky to be welcomed to teach in Mexico City, Barcelona, Copenhagen, Kyoto, Berlin, London, Amsterdam, and many more places. I visited our rope supplier in Turkey. 

In 2018 wrote a book about macramé that finally paid out the advance this week! Woot! (a new book idea is brewing!)
 

I toured the USA in a mini van with my friend Caitlin teaching over 50 workshops from coast to coast over 3 months to celebrate that book.

I worked with amazing women in the studio and across the world, my teammates and my students who taught me so much about how to lead, how to be kind, how to ask for what you need, and how to be human. I am still learning. You know who you are.

We as a company sold over $3 million worth of rope, classes, and other craft supplies.
 
Our work helped launch the careers of small craft business owners around the globe. - continued in slides and comments

Feels like ☀️ training with this guy lately!

Just about a year ago, I happened to watch some new people train their dogs. I remember I was so impressed. Their sessions started with intention - there was a warm up routine (something completely foreign to me at that point). Then the entire session just flowed effortlessly between obedience and play. There was no awkward down time or disengagement between the handler and the dog. The dogs looked so happy to be working and the handlers were clear and focused in their communication. I remember thinking, wow, how do we get on that level 🤩

Fast forward to 2024 and it feels like we are finally making some moves! There’s still a ton of work to do, but I’ve been so grateful to learn from some super talented teams these past few months. ➡️ Leaping into the future to see what the kitchen will look like later this year 🤸‍♀️👀🥹

I’m obsessed with these renderings of the space and the way the kitchen design came together from @strucksured 😍

We have made some changes since these were rendered over a year ago, but the general feel of the space remains the same. Warm, cozy, welcoming, and with big bright windows!

If anyone is curious, the changes were:

📝 White cabinets will be a light sage green color instead
📝 Hood vent will be sloped rather than straight
📝 We added some glass fronts to the cabinets on either side of the big window trio
📝 The drawer pulls were swapped for a more old-world-looking pull
📝 We added an arch to the doorway from the kitchen to the hallway

It’s been SO insane seeing this space take shape, bit by bit, right in front of me after imagining it for so many years. We started the design process for the house back in 2020, and in some ways it feels like it’s gone by in a flash, and in other ways it feels like it’s taken forever lol 😂

But I’m incredibly grateful that all the hard work has resulted in a real solid structure taking shape before our eyes!

I can’t wait to share more about budgeting for design choices in a blog post soon (working on it at the moment, hoping to have it up next week! 🤞) In the meantime, have a wonderful leap day my friend!!!

PS—Don’t let fear keep you from taking a wild, ridiculous leap. With some work + a dash of stubbornness, you never know where it might take you! 😊

I made this braised chicken without any electricity in the house because the power was out during a storm, so I can testify that all you need to make it is a functioning burner on your stovetop 🔥👍🤣

The color in the dish comes from my power-spice-combo of curry powder and paprika, which are two of my all-time favorite spices. They go SO well with the comforting flavor of chicken & the chunky sweet carrots, and they also compliment the rich and slightly tangy flavor of Greek yogurt, which is used to add some creaminess and even more flavor to the sauce 🤌

You can find the recipe at AdventuresInCooking.com or comment CARROT and I’ll message you a link! 🍲

I always prefer to use either soaked and pureed cashews or Greek yogurt to add creaminess to sauces, the fermentation process of creating yogurt neutralizes a lot of the compounds in dairy that can cause stomach irritability (at least in my case!) so I can still enjoy the flavor and texture without the tummy ache.

Plus there’s loads of fresh herbs and other flavorful veggies like onions, garlic, and green onions, too! Can’t wait for you to enjoy it, my friend!! 😋🧡

Standing in our wintery future bedroom with....WINDOWS!! ➡️🪟 We had *crazy* storms and a LOT of snowfall a couple weeks ago, and luckily @hainlineconstruction was able to get the windows in beforehand, which helped keep a lot of snow from blowing into the house. 🌬️

So crazy happy and grateful for this peaceful wild place 🙂 Wishing you all a wonderful week!

Yep, you’re seeing that right—a rotisserie function in your own oven! 😱

Out of all the many features of my @appliancesconnection @ilveusa Majestic range, THIS is the one that realllllly blew my mind 🤯 Normally I’m not one for fancy gadgets, but this had me jumping up and down like a small child because I was so excited!! 🤸

Caramelized onion rolls, meet the most wonderful time of the year (and by that I mean mid-winter where you eat lots of delicious carbs because you’re stuck inside and the weather is driving you crazy so why not! 😜)

As far as homemade rolls go, these are really simple and easy to make. Don’t let the alluring fancy spiral pattern fool you! It’s just a straightforward kneading of dough ingredients together, followed by a rise.

Then you roll out the dough, spread the lovely caramelized onions all over it, roll it up, slice it, let it rise a bit more, and then bake it. And voila! Caramelized onion rolls at your service, ready to soothe any winter-induced stress or anxiety you may be feeling. Don’t you just love carbs? 🧅🍞

The recipe is in the archives at AdventuresInCooking, or you can comment ONION below and I’ll dm you a link to the recipe 💌

We had severe storms here in Portland this past week. They were forecast to be a couple days...and then turned into a week-long barrage of ice and winds and subzero temperatures. We lost power for a day, which is nothing compared to other folks in our city who had no power for 5+ days.

I’m grateful that the storm has passed, and the worst thing that happened in our household was mild frostbite on one of our chicken’s combs. She got it on the first night of the storm so we’ve kept her inside since then and it’s healing up nicely. (It’s Bebe, which is the same chicken who survived a raccoon attack this past summer. It’s been one helluva year for this poor weathered ol’ gal). 🐔♥️

Wishing you all a cozy weekend + stay safe my dear friends!!

Brightening up winter with a vibrant + refreshing @empress1908gin Grapefruit Gimlet, made with Empress Elderflower Rose Gin, fresh grapefruit juice, grapefruit simple syrup, and a splash of bubbles! 🍊

I love Empress Elderflower Rose Gin with citrus especially, the gin itself is distilled with orange peels, rose petals, elderflower, and other delicious aromatics that pair SO well with bright winter citrus 🙌

It gets its lovely color naturally from the rose petals and black carrot used in the distilling process, and it has the loveliest spice notes and a subtle sweetness to it that I’m kiiiind of obsessed with 🤩

Enjoy the recipe for this delicious ray of sunshine below, my friends! Cheers!!

🍊 Grapefruit Simple Syrup

½ cup sugar
½ cup water
3 tablespoons fresh squeezed grapefruit juice

In a small pot, simmer together sugar and water for 10 minutes, add grapefruit juice & stir to combine. Take off heat, allow to cool, then refrigerate.

🍊 Grapefruit Gimlet Fizz (serves 2)

4 ounces @empress1908gin (1/2 cup)
2 ounces grapefruit juice (¼ cup)
2 ounce grapefruit simple syrup (¼ cup)
2 ounces sparkling mineral water
Rosemary sprig for garnish

Combine #EmpressGin, grapefruit juice, and syrup together in a large mixing glass and stir to combine. Evenly distribute between two coupe glasses, top with sparkling water, garnish with rosemary sprig, and enjoy!

Tem muscle car mais icônico que esse??

O Superbird foi desenvolvido em túnel de vento para demonstrar a superioridade da Chrysler Corporation nas competições da NASCAR. A intenção era poder entrar na concessionária e poder levar para casa um modelo semelhante ao usado nas clássicas provas de corrida americanas 🇺🇸 

Estamos falando de uma versão modificada do Road Runner, projetado com traços do irmão Dodge Charger Daytona Talladega, mas ainda mais aerodinâmico. O objetivo dos dois era vencer o Ford Torifo e vencer na NASCAR.

O Superbird recebeu esse nome por sua associação ao desenho animado Road Runner (do papa-léguas). O nome aparece em um adesivo colocado nas laterais das aletas verticais do aerofólio traseiro, assim como uma imagem do personagem do desenho animado segurando um capacete de corrida.

Na década de 60, a NASCAR exigia que os veículos a serem usados nas corridas tinham de estar disponíveis para o público no geral e ser vendidas pelo menos 500 unidades, um requisito conhecido como homologação.

Porém com a virada para o ano 1970, foi aumentada a exigência para uma unidade produzida para cada 2 revendedores do fabricante nos EUA. Isso significou para a Plymouth a productives 1920 unidades do Superbird. Logo, como 1970 foi seu único ano de produção, faz desse muscle car ser uma verdadeira lenda 🤩

Que tal começar o mês com uma curiosidade? Hoje vamos falar sobre um detalhe incrível que pode fazer toda a diferença no desempenho de um carro: os famosos beadlocks! 🚀🔧

Você já ouviu falar nesse nome? É uma tecnologia que vai além do visual diferentão, trazendo benefícios reais para a performance de um veículo preparado. Mas afinal, o que são esses beadlocks e por que eles são tão importantes?

Os beadlocks são esses vários parafusos que têm a função de prender o pneu ao aro de forma supersegura, permitindo que se ande com libras mais baixas e que se aumente a área de contato dos pneus com o asfalto em arrancadas poderosas.

Isso significa que você terá uma tração mais eficiente, garantindo um desempenho ainda melhor! E sem se preocupar com qualquer possibilidade de destalonamento… É como ter uma segurança extra para explorar todo o potencial do seu carro, sem medo de contratempos.

Agora que vocês sabem o que são os beadlocks e como eles podem potencializar a performance do seu carro, me contem: vocês já conheciam essa tecnologia?

Exclusive #EarthDay video: Photographers David Wilson and Mike Theiss from Sundiver Snorkel Tours went on a mission to document marine life at the reefs after weeks of quarantined conditions due to the Covid-19 virus. Some of the coral reefs offshore of #KeyLargo haven’t experienced boat traffic nor human visitors for many weeks. Will this help our chances of documenting the elusive spotted eagle ray ? We used drones to monitor the area and within minutes discovered a large group of several dozen spotted eagle rays, also known as a “fever”. We were able to track the eagle rays with drones and quickly deployed into the water and snorkeled right up next to the them. They were beautiful and looked like birds flying under the water. Mission accomplished!

Video by: @ExtremeNature and @DavidHasTattoos

Special Thanks to @Sundiver for making all this possible. When the quarantine conditions are lifted and it’s safe to travel again, head down to Key Largo, Florida to see this amazing marine life in person while snorkeling with Sundiver Snorkel Tours www.SnorkelTickets.com

Back in the days the visual update for the AMG GT coupé and roadster includes new front and tail lamps as well as a new design idiom for the tailpipe trims. The new light controls of the LED High Performance headlights now display parallels with the AMG GT 4-Door Coupé and therefore further strengthen the AMG GT family connection with the two-door models. A tri-functional, arched light guide takes on the functions of daytime running light, navigation light and turn signals.

The light of the LED tail lights also appears even deeper set and sportier through the dark background.
From the back the new look of the rear apron is striking, its sporty black diffuser insert was redesigned for the AMG GT, AMG GT S and AMG GT C. The twin tailpipe trims are now adapted to the lines of the AMG GT 4-Door Coupé ‑ round on the AMG GT and trapezoidal on the AMG GT S and AMG GT C. The rear design of the AMG GT R keeps its distinctive shape.

The AMG GT and AMG GT S are getting a new black grained sill cover on the bottom section. This makes for an extra-dynamic look. In conjunction with optional exterior packages, trim elements add individual highlights in high-gloss black, matt black, high-gloss chrome or carbon fibre.
Also, on request, the AMG GT and AMG GT S are available with a new y-spoke light-alloy wheel in matt black with a high-sheen finish. AMG GT Black Series „The Endgame“.

Back in the days, the most powerful AMG V8 series engine of all time, the most expressive design, the most elaborate aerodynamics, the most intelligent material mix, the most distinctive driving dynamics: For the new Mercedes-AMG GT Black Series (combined fuel consumption 12.8 l/100 km, combined CO2 emissions 292 g/km)[1], the Affalterbach designers have pulled out all the stops when it comes to the art of vehicle design.

The super sports car perfectly embodies the brand’s rich tradition in motorsport, as well its many years of expertise in developing complete vehicles which impress in every respect. The result is an output of 537 kW (730 hp) from a V8 engine with a ‚flat‘ crankshaft, combined with active aerodynamics and a design which stems directly from the current AMG GT3 racing car.

Different designs of V8 engines.

The design of a V8 engine gives designers plenty of room to play with in one key element: the crank arrangement on the crankshaft.
The result is the most powerful V8 series engine from Mercedes-AMG.

The GT Black Series engine may be based on the AMG 4.0-litre V8 biturbo engine with dry sump lubrication, but it has been given the new internal code M178 LS2 due to the numerous modifications. It achieves 730hp at 6700-6900 rpm and delivers a maximum torque of 800Nm at 2000-6000 rpm. New camshafts and exhaust manifolds are adapted to the new firing order and further improve the gas cycle.

Both twin scroll exhaust turbochargers are mounted in anti-friction bearings, as in the top-of-the-range four-door AMG GT Coupé, which optimises their throttle response even further. However, in the Black Series, the turbochargers have been given a larger compressor wheel, meaning that both can deliver a total of 1100 kg air per hour.

Mercedes-AMG One man, one engine 
Handcrafted by Michael Kübler @f1mike28 in Germany Affalterbach. Driving Performance is my Passion! Mercedes-AMG the Performance and Sports Car Brand from Mercedes-Benz and Exclusive Partner for Pagani Automobili. Mercedes-AMG Handcrafted by Racers.

.
Lençóis Maranhenses is located in northeastern Brazil, this unique national park unveils a mesmerizing landscape that seems like a blend of dreams and reality. Vast expanses of pristine, white sand dunes stretch as far as the eye can see, interrupted only by crystalline lagoons scattered like jewels in the desert. 
During the rainy season these lagoons form, creating a contrast between the azure waters and the pristine sand. 
The best time to go is between June and September, as during this time there is usually enough water from the past rainy season.

Neuquén! Hace más de 40 años que pateo tus calles y conozco a parte de tus familias, tus álamos y tu río Limay. Fue un gran abrazo infinito de amor este concierto inolvidable que jamás se irá de mi corazón. Recuerdo la primera gira solista en el año 85 en el Club Pacífico, si la memoria no me falla, tocando como si fuera la última vez para no más de treinta personas y hoy este lago interminable que construimos en el tiempo también cantando, bailando y escuchándonos como si fuera el último concierto. Gracias a @pitifernandez20 a @solojuanse y a @fabitacontenta. Hicieron todo más bello y cálido.
La semana que viene comienza la preparación del nuevo álbum que hoy me confirmaron se grabará en los estudios Abbey Road en el mes de julio de este año con la coproducción de @gusborner y @oliverodiego. 
Toda mi dedicación estará puesta ahora en terminar de componer un álbum que llevo conmigo hace muchos años y si todo sale bien también tendrá su película. 
Mi amor y gratitud infinita hacia toda la familia que acompaña en el viaje alrededor del mundo. Seguimos en nuestra tour de force.

What a day.
A match made in heaven.
Alain Arnoux flying low over the river of sand that flows across the Sahara, in the far north of Chad.

This week the USDA announced that there are fewer farms in the U.S. than at any time since 1850, and 40% of them are owned by people over age 65.  In most industrialized countries, farmers are less than 2% of the population and shrinking.  Here, Doug Hellinger is driving a weed sprayer past the homestead that his grandmother established near Shelby, Montana, shortly after 1909, when the Homestead Act gave 320 acres for free if you farmed the land for five years.  At that time, there were 72 families per 36 sq miles, and today, just 8 people remain, including Doug.

Always good to have friends in high places.  I had the easy job on this helicopter shoot for @nytmag a few years ago, with @jimmychin hanging over the rail while photographing a maintenance worker climbing up the antenna of One World Trade. Jimmy and his amazing wife @chaivasarhelyi have gone on to scale the heights of Hollywood, but when I ran into Jimmy last week he sheepishly declared “I’m still just a dirtbag climber.” Aren’t we all?

Looking for covers for my next book today, and I came across this forgotten image from the soybean harvest in Brazil two years ago.  Soybean production in Brazil is almost ten times what it was in 1985, and those numbers continue to rise to meet China’s growing demand for pig food. Much of that new production is from land that was once forest.

Volcanic crater of Wau al Namus (hole of mosquitos) in Arabic. 
This massive volcano can easily be seen in satellite views of Southern Libya, as a large black smear in the wind-scoured sands of the Sahara.  The inner crater is bordered by a chain of small salt lakes which are sumps for underground springs). Outside the rim are small black dunes of windblown volcanic ejecta.  It was difficult getting there with my motorized paraglider during the time of Gadaffi, but would be even more complicated today. Carpe diem!
So nice to see my photo above the fold on front page of today’s @NYTimes!  To see more and read the story on-line, go to link in bio.
Herding over 600 sheep down from the remote high pasture of the Aletsch Glacier Valley in Switzerland.  So happy to see this story about the effects of climate change in the Alps in today’s @nytimes

Herding 145,000 sheep and goats onto a livestock carrier in the port of Berbera, Somaliland last July for shipment to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, where 2.6 million animals were ritually sacrificed on the third day of the Hajj pilgrimage.  According to today’s @NYTimes, Somaliland has just granted military use of this sleepy deepwater port to landlocked Ethiopia, allowing access to the busy shipping lanes of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden.  No monetary terms were disclosed, but the deal makes Ethiopia the first nation to recognize the sovereignty of Somaliland, a self-declared democratic republic in one of the world’s poorest regions.  Last year, live animal exports were 85% of Somaliland’s export earnings and 30% of its GDP, but that may be about to change.

Snowmobile with sled passing under the Atyrau Bridge on the frozen Yesil River, Astana, Kazakhstan.  The bridge was designed by young local architects who were inspired by the shape of the endemic Caspian Sturgeon.

City of poets and travellers, the capital of Ireland is a city full of charm and vitality ☘️

@staycityaparthotels City Centre is the perfect accommodation to visit the city🔝
A small studio apartment with everything you need for a comfortable stay, with a rich breakfast of fresh products 👍

The attractions not to be missed:
▶️Guinness Storehouse, the historic brewery of 1759, today a seven-story high museum complex with the Gravity Bar on top and its spectacular 360-degree views over the rooftops of Dublin
▶️Trinity Collage, the oldest and most prestigious university in Ireland, with the Old Library, a beautiful oak library that houses 200,000 volumes including the Book of Kells, a precious illuminated manuscript
▶️Temple Bar, the historic district full of pubs
▶️ Christ Church Cathedral, a wonderful cathedral built in the heart of medieval Dublin, built on the site of a Viking wooden church

From here you can easily reach:
▶️the spectacular Giants Causeway, one of the most magical places in Ireland with 40.000 hexagonal basalt columns, of volcanic origin⛰️

▶️the Old Bushmills Distillery, the oldest licensed whiskey distillery in the world, where you can have a truly unique whiskey tasting 🥃

▶️take an exciting tour along wild cliffs 🧗‍♀️

Mayıs’ta kavuşuyoruz 🏔️🫠 En unutamadığım yolculuğumu sorduklarında Everest Ana Kamp Yürüyüşünü hep ilk sırada söylüyorum. (ve bunun Everest Dağı ile çok da alakası yok)

4 Mayıs’ta @sayga.travel misafirlerine Cihan ve ben eşlik edeceğiz. Emin olun rahatınız için her şeyi düşündük. Kathmandu’dan yürüyüşün başlayacağı noktaya helikopterlerle geçiyoruz. Ana Kamp’tan geriye de helikopterler ile dönüyoruz. Yürürken de ve uçarken de nefesiniz kesilecek.🧡🏔️

Bu arada en sevdiğim yolculuk olmasının Everest Dağı ile alakası yok derken söylemek istediğim; bu yürüyüşe Everest Ana Kampı görmek için başlıyorsun ama yolda gördüklerin, düşündüklerin, aldığın kararlar, vazgeçtiklerin, Himalayalarda küçücük bir detay olman,  başka bir dünyayı görmen seni çok güzel törpülüyor.
Umarım bunu bşr gün kendiniz de yazarsınız 🙏🏼🙌🏼🏔️

Turun  detayları için lütfen @sayga.travel ‘a yazın

Mükemmel bir kamp deneyimi nasıl olabilirse öyle oldu🫠 Biraz iddialı olacak ama böyle bir etkinliğe ev sahipliği yaptığım için gururluyum da.

Sandras Dağı ve Gökova Körfezi’nde iki farklı lokasyondaydık. #ColumbiaDeneyimi için @columbiasportswear_tr ekibi ile birlikte şahane 2 gün geçirdik.
Trekking yaptık, kano ile gezdik, olta attık, hatta kanoda balık tutmayı ‘denedik’, igloo yapımını öğrendik, hediklerle yürüdük. Bunlar daha ilk gündü. Bu videodan sonra bir de ikinci günün videosu gelecek yani.

En önemli kısım bence soğuk havadaki konforu test ettiğimiz Sandras Dağı’ydı. Burada OmniHeat Infinity teknolojisine sahip ürünleri denedik. İşte tam burada acayip bir gelişme ile denk geldik.
15 Şubat’ta uzaya gönderilen ve şu anda Ay’a doğru hareket eden Odysseus uzay aracı ABD’nin 50 yıl aradan sonra Ay’a inecek ilk aracı. Ay’daki kalıcı üs için ekipman taşıyor şu an. Bu aracı Ay’da güneşin kavurucu ışınlarından koruyacak olan (gündüzleri sıcaklık 120°C’yi bulabiliyor.) koruyucu ekipman Columbia OmniHeat Infinity ‘nin ta kendisi. Yani giydiğimiz mont, pantolon ve botlardaki teknolojinin aynısı.
Nasa’nın 1964’te geliştirdiği uzay battaniyesinden ilham aldıkları teknolojiyi geliştirerek şu an Nasa görevi için gitmiş bir araca bu desteği sunabilecek hale getirmişler. Mükemmel.. 🙌🏼💯

Hikayeler kaybolmadan bir göz atmanızı ısrarla tavsiye ederim.
@exploremugla ekibine de organize ettikleri deneyimler için teşekkürler.
(#columbia işbirliği)

Giderken “acaba mı?” dedim, yalan değil. Çünkü çok çok meşhur. İnsan şüphelenmeden edemiyor bu yüzden. Motokichi Yukimura haklı bir üne sahip bence🧡🙌🏼

Nasıldı? Güzeldi ve eğlenceliydi.
İçeri girdiğinizden itibaren sizi içine çeken bir show gibi. En meşhur yemeği #omurice ‘ı hazırlarken tüm aşamaları tek tek açıklıyor, tarifini veriyor. Dikkat çekici hareketleriyle de süslüyor işi. Japonların en sevdiğim özelliği yaptıkları işe tapar gibi tutunmaları galiba. Bu adamda da çılgınlık yaparken mükemmeliyetçiliği korumaya çalışan bir tavır var. 

Yumurtayı fried rice üstüne koyarken size
-cutting?
-flying?
diye soruyor.
Cutting tahmin ettiğiniz gibi omleti bıçakla yardığı versiyon.
Flying ise videoda sonlara doğru göründüğü gibi, omleti tabağa fırlatıyor ve hooop açılıyor.
Üstüne döktüğü dömi glas sos ise umami bombası gibi 🫠🤤 Onun da tarifini vermiş bir ara. Reddit’te gördüm.

Every time I go to #Finland I come back a little more playful and a little more curious in the best possible way. It’s actually really hard to put this magic into words but it’s a really special place.

Last year I travelled to #OulankaNationalPark to experience the trip curated by @exodustravels that combined the best of winter activities with a real tangible purpose. Whilst exploring we were sampling the rivers for eDNA, which is a relatively new technology to monitor and record local biodiversity.

For me, having had the privilege of travelling the world, the purpose of this trip really sets it a cut above a regular holiday.

Flew to the land down under few days ago and I finally got to see Canberra. I must say this beautiful city is more quiet and laidback as compared to the vibrant and busy Sydney.

With many things in mind, visiting the National Gallery of Australia is on the top our list. Inside it we saw a lot of amazing masterpieces, but what struck me the most is James Turrell's 'Within without' Skyspace, a viewing chamber (or a "stupa") highlighted by turquoise water that surrounds it. This work shows the way we percieve the sky depending on the time of the day. They say it is at its most dramatic and complex form during dawn and dusk, marking the transition between day and night. Truly a remarkable work of art where nature, art, and architecture meet!

Excited to share more snaps and stories from the many things we saw and learned about this city. Big thanks to my travel partner @bigskynationph for keeping us connected everywhere we go with their travel wi-fi!

The beetle of rebirth 🪲🌞
At the end of November 2021 we were at a friends house about to leave when a golden beetle posed on my hand. It had been a long time since I saw one or at least payed close attention to it. I feel that many times we experience things often but don’t really give importance to them until we feel it is needed, then it becomes something meaningful. I started drawing the beetle on my notebook, carefully placed the insect on my finger it was holding my index with his tiny legs and thought about a ring! 
It gave me nostalgia of when the world was different and when we could travel, reminded me of our time in Egypt and in some way gave me hope, Cairo 2019 was also where I first saw a beetle ring from Tutankamon in the museum. I was amazed by Egyptian culture, art and mostly jewelry I thought it was cool but I never really questioned the symbolism of the elements and characters they used back then and why, but that day the golden beetle that posed on my hand made me curious and I started reaserching what it means, the meaning varies depending the culture but what I took from the Egyptians is that: the beetle symbolized the sun, a new day, a new opportunity, a cicle, knowing that the sun rises every day no matter what, rebirth! I thought the meaning was beautiful and felt like the right timing for me to start a process of “rebirth” this was right before 2021 ended, 

which had been a though year, I was not feeling too motivated, my grandma had just passed away a couple months before, and some little struggles that made me feel a bit stuck and not at my best. I didn’t know it at the time but from that day it was going to take 5 months to have the finished ring in my hands. Not because the actual process takes that long but in a way I wanted to have it ready whenever I felt better with myself, finishing this ring will mean to have a rebirth in a way, learnt the lessons, feel more motivated and in a better mental space. 
(more of the story in the comments :)

Playa Paraíso fue elegida como la más bonita de México, por los lectores de la revista especializada en turismo “México Desconocido”.
Sólo superada por la ciudad de Quebec, Canadá, Mérida también fue clasificada como la ciudad más segura de América Latina.

Chichén Itzá significa "boca del pozo de los itzaes", en alusión al cenote situado al norte de la pirámide y que era considerado un enclave sagrado, además de una fuente de agua dulce esencial para aquella ciudad de templos y sabios astrónomos.
Isla en Quintana Roo, México. Fue el primer lugar que los españoles descubrieron de México (Nueva España).

Yacimiento arqueológico de la cultura maya precolombina, localizado en el sureste de México, en el territorio que hoy es el estado de Quintana Roo, unos noventa kilómetros al este de Chichén Itzá y unos cuarenta al noroeste de Tulum.

Hoy en día son uno de los destinos favoritos de los viajeros, pues en la península de Yucatán existen más de mil cenotes. En esta ocasión visitamos el “Cenote Azul” que se encuentra al sur de Playa del Carmen, como a 20 minutos aproximadamente si vas en automóvil.

I saw @karlieplace post a bit of this editing style on a reel yesterday and I just thought it was amazing. Shout out to hers, you should definitely go check it out. 

When I see the dodge/burn notes on old film prints it’s a reminder that the art and intention of the shot doesn’t end until it’s delivered. I imagine some people would rather enjoy the magic without seeing how the sausage is made but I LOVE editing and always have.

I came up in this industry at a time where there was this odd mystique and elitism that I thankfully avoided, but I saw it discourage SO many people. And there was a tension because my income was also tied to education regarding editing and presets, and carving out a brand that was uniquely my voice. I’d much rather contribute to the shared pool of liberating knowledge so that the beautiful thing you were meant to do is not trapped behind something as dull as tone curves and split toning. 

The anchors of journalistic integrity are different than those for eliciting emotion. But you are also free to, and encouraged to, be unashamed about what does and doesn’t land with your creative preference. Just don’t make that the primary thing about your engagements with people on the internet. 

As always if you have questions about my process, whether it be gear, software, how I think about what I do, or anything else I’d so much rather communicate than get a ‘like’.
For what few days we get, what a joy it is that we got to touch grass and watch the wild sky.

Epic southern breakfast situation going down at @surfasla today until 2pm! @calabama and @chefgreeny collaborated on a pimento cheese and fried balogna breakfast sandwich for @biite.club and it is just as soul warming as it sounds. Don’t blow it! Go get a sandwich, some cheese and of course some SAUCE.

Whatever the question was, @katorestaurant is the answer.

Still thinking about my visit to their new DTLA space. After 6 visits to the OG west side Kato (and two unique pandemic takeouts!), I was beyond thrilled for the team to take their talents to the Row DTLA, allowing them to be bigger and better than ever. The BYOB has been replaced by an absolutely phenomenal bar program with innovative cocktails and an unbelievable wine list. The dishes have never been better, this current menu is without a doubt my favorite they’ve ever created. the uni donut with jamon, the A5 wagyu, the caviar with geoduck and spinach (!)… MAN! 😱 The service has always been a standout, but like everything else they’ve leveled that up too.

What can I say? If you’ve been following me you know how much I love @jonyao’s cooking and all I can say is somehow it’s getting even better. They are big time now, so they are charging accordingly, but I will not mince words here: it is worth every penny. This is a place worthy of a a celebration… and worthy of celebrating. Congrats to @jonyao @dogsaget and the rest of the crew on the move. Y’all are a blessing.

Do yourself a favor. First, follow @breakfast_dreams. Then, keep an eye out for his schedule. Make plans. Circle the day on your calendar. Then wait patiently until that day comes and you can wrap your hands around the breakfast sandwich of your dreams.

Watching the assembly of these sandwiches was like watching an artist at work. The delicate way the cheese was placed on the SIXTY MINUTE sous vide egg. And can we talk about the bacon? Because we were all definitely talking about the bacon. Cap it off with his homemade fermented Calabrian Chile hot sauce and you have got a day that’s just been made.

Sometimes, you might even get lucky and stumble upon them doing a collab, like they did today with @aglscraftmeats. The Glizzy Dream Special featured a Butter Toasted Martin's Potato Roll, Dream Spread, Sous Vide Egg, American Cheese, Smoked Onions & Peppers and AGL's Smoked Serrano and Oaxacan Chili Sausage. It was… heaven. One of those times you really have to live in the moment knowing this is a one time thing.

In all seriousness, it was truly awesome to finally meet @liljoshygram and try his cooking after being #InternetFriends for so long. It was just extra special that the food was so damn good.

While I’m letting this pre-workout kick in, here’s a photo dump of the best food I ate in the last 30 days, my own cooking not included!

1. Unbelievable meal at @horsesonsunset. That burger. That panino. That Boudin Basque. That chocolate tart. Already have another res.
2. Celebratory meal at @alldaybabyla featuring this absurd malted chive waffle with smoked whitefish dish and caviar and one of @thessa.diadem’s mini key lime pies for breakfast the next day.
3. Made @kylandent wake up at 6:45 on a Saturday to get @courage_bagels before he headed back to San Diego and we were up until 1:30 the night before. Worth it.
4. Discovered I live a few blocks from some amazing Thai fusion food. Been craving the Heavent Scent extra spicy from @spiceseasonstudiocity ever since.
5. The cavatelli at @jonandvinnydelivery may be their best pasta. Yeah I said it.
6. My therapist is a block from @mariscosjalisco so looks like I’m going to be indulging in their legendary shrimp tacos twice a month.
7. Finally, @burgershewrote__. LA gets yet another smash burger, no I’m not mad about it.

48 hours in Buffalo photo dump #letsgobuffalo

While I was there specifically to pit my old butt off to @everytimeidie, you know I had to make the most of the few meals I was able to fit it that weren’t at the venue. Think I did well. 

Everything was fantastic but the highlight was definitely going 30 min out of town to @barbilltavern for a Beef on Weck and hot wings.
🦐NOLA photo dump. Filled the void with food, my body may never recover.

Photo Dump: Highlights From Things I’ve Eaten In The Last 6 Weeks.

I’ll admit, sometimes I struggle quite a bit. Life ain’t easy, and sometimes it feels harder than it might be, and round these parts we accept that mental health should be a priority despite not doing enough to make it so. 

So, making this silly photo dump reminded me of some really great memories over the past 6 weeks: Taking my folks to @jonandvinnydelivery for the first time, my monthly dinners with my cousin at 
@baveldtla and @alldaybabyla, a fun @primepizzala Halloween in with my wife, brother and his fiancé, curating a birthday burger crawl to @amboy_qualitymeats, pregaming in an elite way for concerts and Dodger games at @goldburgerla and @elcompadrerestaurants, and bringing a tast of Philly to my stepdad when his trip got canceled via @tommydinics and @goldbelly.

A little blip of light between therapy appointments. 😜

Sometimes a work lunch is a protein bar. But sometimes work lunch is a phenomenal meal at @angeliniosteria. Those times are clearly better.

LA is truly becoming the food capitol of the country. They’re coming for your bagels, they’re coming for your hot chicken, they’re coming for your pasta, and NOW they’re coming for your BBQ, and @mooscraftbarbecue is absolutely as good as it gets. The brisket, the pork ribs, the sausage, the corn, the mac, the slaw… all 10/10. Bonus points for a great draft beer list. Things that happen in bed... 🫦 You spend more time in bed than you think, so why not transform your bed into a tranquil oasis? These are some of the tips that could help you achieve that.
• Quality Bedding. Invest in high-quality, comfortable sheets that are soft and breathable. My favorite ones are bamboo lyocell sheets from @cariloha’s Retreat Collection.
• Aesthetics. Choose calming, neutral colors for your bedding, like white or ivory. Avoid printed sheets to create a serene atmosphere.
• Pillows. Use memory foam pillows for added comfort, especially if you are struggling with neck pain.
• Mattress Topper. Enhance the comfort of your mattress with a high-quality mattress topper that will provide extra cushioning.
• Dim Lighting. Warm-toned light bulbs help to create a cozy and calming atmosphere.
• Blackout Curtains. These can help block out morning light when you want to sleep in and create a more peaceful sleep environment.
• Aromatherapy. As for scented candles, pick the ones with calming fragrances like lavender, chamomile, or eucalyptus.
• Humidifier. It will help with your skin dryness and improve the quality of your sleep as you’ll start breathing more freely.
• Soft Rugs. Stepping onto a cushiony surface in the morning is a grounding experience that will help start the day on a positive note.
• Electronic Devices. Limit phone usage before bedtime as the blue light radiated from screens can interfere with your sleep.

The truth about ALMOND CROISSANTS🥐

Croissants go stale so quickly!! So here’s what you can do when you have a few extra ones laying around :) Or if you don’t want to pay the almond croissant premium LOL.

✨Ingredients:
•1 cup water
•1/3 cup sugar

•4 croissants
•25 gr unsalted butter
•60 gr cane sugar
•60 gr almond flour
•1 medium egg
•1 tsp vanilla extract
•sliced almonds
•powder sugar for dusting

In a small saucepan, bring water and 1/3 cup of sugar to a boil to make a syrup. Cool down. Preheat oven 350°F and cut croissants in half. In a bowl, combine softened unsalted butter with sugar. Then add almond flour, combine, and lastly add egg and vanilla to form an almost paste. Brush sugar syrup on the inside and outside of the croissant and then spread the almond paste inside. Close the croissant and spread more paste on top and top off with sliced almonds. Bake for 15-18 mins, cool down, and dust with powdered sugar. Enjoy!
