Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for eastern black rhinos, establishing a vital breeding population of 21 rhinos at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century. But moving a black rhino, an animal weighing over a ton, is a Herculean challenge fraught with danger at every turn. It begins with the risky task of sedating the massive creature, a procedure that requires precision and caution to ensure both the rhino’s safety and that of the vets and handlers. Once subdued, the real test begins as the sedated rhino must be carefully revived and maneuvered into a sturdy crate, a task made all the more daunting by the animal’s immense size and strength. Every step of this delicate operation underscores the inherent risks involved. Watch the sheer force this rhino unleashes as he awakens and imagine doing this 20 more times over the course of 2 weeks. The teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication.  In an ideal world, we wouldn’t have to go through these extreme measures but with approximately 80% of the world’s remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya’s efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures.

I want to sincerely thank all the people you see here and their partners and encourage you to follow @nature_africa @nature_org @loisaba_conservancy @kenyawildlifeservice  @olpejeta @sandiegozoo @spaceforgiants  @earthrangertech @elewanacollection @lewaconservancy @dr_mathew_mutinda_ 

Video by @amivitale

#Loisaba #LoisabaConservancy #LandConnectedLifeProtected #BlackRhinos #RhinoConservation #ConservationSuccess #EndangeredSpecies #Wildlife #RhinoRecovery #Rhinos #conservation

I am humbled to share another remarkable conservation story from Kenya: the resurgence of eastern black rhinos from the brink of extinction. In a pivotal moment, Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for these creatures, establishing a vital breeding population at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century mainly due to poaching and long ago,  trophy hunting. This first image shows the moment a rhino was resuscitated after it stopped breathing and quickly released. The arduous tasks of tracking, darting, and relocating 21 of these critically endangered giants, each weighing over a ton, posed formidable challenges, yet the teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication. Their efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures. The final image shows the skull of the last rhino poached in the 1970s resting beneath a celestial canopy, symbolizing this hopeful shift as Kenya now stands  as a nation that is expanding habitat and bolstering rhino populations. With approximately 80% of the world's remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya is safeguarding endangered populations for future generations. 

I want to sincerely thank all the partners and encourage you to follow @nature_africa @nature_org @loisaba_conservancy  @kenyawildlifeservice  @olpejeta @sandiegozoo @spaceforgiants  @elewanacollection @lewaconservancy

📌Why is joint mobility important? (Read bellow⬇️) Video is speed up 3x for reels let me know in the comments if you prefer this format or would like to see normal speed as a carrousel format.🎥 
 
The way I see it, “Mobility” Is kind of like a collaboration effort between our muscles and joints.
 
When our joint mobility is limited, we might be missing out on opportunities to be stronger, more athletic, and more efficient.
 
The ability to move our joints through their full range helps our muscles work more optimally, and when our muscles can do their work, they can also get stronger and help keep our joints healthy in return.
 
💪🏼Having a good balance between strength and joint mobility helps distribute the stress more evenly through the body instead of overstressing our joints (back, hips, knees, ankles, etc.).
 
🚪Our joints are kind of like the hinges to a door; if that door remains unopened for long periods in addition to environmental decay, the hinges in that door will start creaking and get rusty overtime. In our case, it will be arthritis, bursitis, inflammation, and things like that.
 
So you see, just as with the door example, maintenance and movement were keys to extending the life and function of it, in our case, MAINTENANCE and MOVEMENT are also keys to a BETTER QUALITY OF LIFE.🙌🏼

STAY ACTIVE!💪🏼

#mobilitytraining #hipmobility #hipmobilitywork 
#jointhealth #bodyweighttraining #spinemobility #wellnessjourney #homeworkouts

Some days there is no plan. I just wanted to move a little so I did and it ended up being a light weight mobility exploration day.

Energy levels where on the low with some #Adenomyosis aches and pains in the mix. I wasn’t looking to exhaust myself in a long workout and risk feeling super tired afterwards. So I just moved for a bit, worked on some areas that I wanted to target and moved on with the rest of my day.

At the end I was feeling accomplished and still had energy to do other things the rest of the day. 

The are days I push and days I back down, IS MY BALANCE. As long as I am making positive progress is a win for me. I just try my best to be consistent with it.

Don’t compare your journey with anyone else’s. 

FIND YOUR BALANCE 🤜🏼🤛🏼

Angkor Wat and park in Siem Reap, Cambodia. This is my second time here and it still feels as mystical as the first time. At the beginning of our tour, our guide overwhelmed us with all the mathematical calculations and engineering ingenuity that went into building Angkor Wat. Certain points of the structure lined up perfectly with the Draco Constellation and the sun positioning at sunset. Although there are educated speculation from experts archeologists saying this dates back about 900 years ago, It’s all a mystery.

On the other hand, Spiritual channelers have mentioned this to be older than 5000 BC. It’s a place to activate the pineal gland (third eye) through frequencies, it’s also an informational point for earth to funnel data to and from other planets/galaxies. It’s like another access point of information like the great pyramids. The art carvings hold a lot of relations to Hinduism on many of the Angkor Park structures. But personally, I see a lot of psychedelic reflections on some of the temples. They almost look like what I see as the crossover realm between the mind and other outer dimensions. It’s like the level where you have to overcome the ego before connecting with your higher self. Very interesting place to walk around and wander off into. 

#southeastasia #cambodia #angkorwat #spiritualjourney

If Saigon is to write a love poem in the form of a coffee shop, this would be it 🥀 A once historical abandon building, now the hot spot for the kids. In the daytime it looks deserted but at night it becomes alive with local art studios, cafe, music, and mystery. 

If you’re not familiar, the boutique cafes in Saigon are endless. Each has its own charismatic touch in the best possible way. Vietnam is the second largest coffee exporter in the world, therefore it’s no surprise that every cafe ☕️ will deliver in strength and caffeine! Vietnam truly runs on coffee.

#saigon #cafe #coffeeculture

Memories in Saigon! 🧡 It’s so chaotic here but I appreciate this city so much more than I did before. Maybe a few weeks more, I will probably come out frazzled and rough around the edges looking like weird Barbie 😵‍💫 This place definitely spit me out feeling a little tougher 💪 To be honest, I did not enjoy my last visit as an adult. I didn’t feel much of a connection back then. It’s funny how we can come to appreciate things that we once overlooked. Traveling again also helps me to appreciate people. Sometimes our environment and people we see often can take away from us, switching up our environment a little can help us enjoy people again. They say the grass is always greener on the other side, but really it’s just getting away from the same stale energy that was taking and not giving. #vietnamtravel #saigon

Make sure to save this info if you’re thinking about visiting Vietnam. We’re in Ben Tre, Vietnam and this has got to be one of the most underrated places we’ve learned about. I hope people keep going to Bali and leave this place for us 😆

This town is 2 hrs south of Saigon - which around $40 Grab ride.  The town itself is pretty developed as in roads and sidewalks, but this is where you can relax from the crazy traffic and roads of Saigon. I think Ben Tre fits the criteria of what many people think of Saigon. It’s a growing city, with no crazy developments, or high rise.  Many restaurants or stores here cater to the locals, so you will get more of an authentic experience. The locals are pretty friendly as long as you are respectful. The kids like to say “hello” to my bf because they want to use their English. They get a good chuckle when he says “hi” in Vietnamese. We usually greet and thanks in the language of the country we’re in, many folks seem to appreciate it.  The young locals speak English well, older people usually don’t. 

We did 3 tours here with @mrbikerbentreboattour , Troy found him on TripAdvisor. We highly recommend his tours. After doing our first private boat tour, we came back for another tour of the town, and then rented bikes from one of the eco lodges/homestays. @mrbikerbentreboattour has been extremely punctual and helpful with us. His tours gives you a sample of the local lifestyle and Vietnamese tradition. We’ve got to visit the small canals off the Mekong river, and private roads of the locals. We did not experienced any upsell, pressure to buy, or nonsense stops on the tours. It felt more educational and you can see the aunties and uncles on his team working diligently to make a good impression for us. We really appreciated our stay here. It’s so walkable around and the local people love coming out after the sun set but that’s when we are asleep 😴 #travelvietnam #bếntre

Ben Tre, Vietnam

Last year, I was in total hermit mode. I was so eager to build my homestead, I couldn’t focus on anything else. I think that is why I am walking everywhere I possibly can in Vietnam. However, today is a biking day! We rented some bikes at an eco homestay through @mrbikerbentreboattour and it was exactly what I needed. It was so much fun  going around the town on our bikes. There were so many fun fruit shops and Sugarcane juice stand. 🍺 We both got a delicious drink off one of the stands for 50 cents and it was absolutely divine! 
Also, I had one of the most amazing Banh Xeo of my life. We found a random farm that also runs a restaurant and they made us the most incredible Banh Xeo.  I’m already sad to think how much I will miss today 🥲 #vietnamtravel #bentre

Today we decided to check out a park in Saigon. Creating a little reference point gives us a little mission to embark on and get our steps in 😊 This is  always a nice way to discover small gems or see places you would not be able to read or watch about. On our walkie walk, we were able to see the contrast in the city. One of my pics shows the old way of living off a stream (how my parents described their life growing up), and behind it are the new skyscrapers. 

As we walked, we discovered more street foods, mini restaurants, and cafes. I got some sugarcane juice off an auntie from a side stall and then stumbled into a little oasis off a super busy bustling road. It was a little coffee stale with lots of unique and local plants surrounding it. Great place for coffee and plant enthusiasts 🪴 There were little tables and seats hidden around an array of hanging plants. Later I found out it was a plant shop too! This was a nice little break stop for another refresher. Troy got his iced coffee and so we got to sit amongst all these pretty greenery. Everything is such a contrast in Saigon. You see old vs new everywhere, the crazy busy hustle of traffic, and Vietnamese taking their naps in the mist of all the chaos in the streets. I really enjoy observing 👀 and wondering how people adapt to the places they live in. 
.

There are so many fun cafes here! My favorite part of the day is going out in the morning to try a new coffee or tea at a new cafe🧡😋 The iced lattes are only around $1 vs $7 in the states 😣 There are like tones of cafes side by side on every block and I am in love with that! ☕️ You also don’t have to worry about people taking up space with their laptops on the tables. At night, the cafes are more bustling with people mingling and sipping on iced tea. If I have more time here, I would probably visit a new coffee shop everyday 🧡

My Barbie moment at a super pink church in Saigon! It’s incredibly hot here but I heard it’s -25 back home, so we’re not complaining! I’ll take this heat and over stimulated city for the time being 🧡 

I thought that crowded places gives me anxiety but what I learned is that the environment and people affect me. Crowded places don’t give me anxiety, the collective energy of the same things do. Sometimes my environment can feel like a drag. People talking about the same things, focused on career, status, gossip, politics, limited beliefs, problems after problems. And when I’m around it too much, it sucks the life force out of me, so I retract. Exploring helps me break free from that. Any sort of traveling, mini trips, or taking off on a plane helps me break free from monotony and repetition. Walking in places is also very grounding for me. I’ve noticed that I need a balance of both worlds, the chaotic city and being in nature. When I become extreme in one, I definitely can feel the lack of balance in my overall energy. We are all different and I’m learning more on how to listen to my personal inner guide. #saigon #vietnam

Anthony Bourdain made a lot of videos  in Vietnam. He definitely created a pathway for international foodies to embrace it’s unique culture. A lot has changed here in development but some of his recommended stops are still around. This place specializes on one of my favorite dishes, Banh Xeo! Banh Xeo looks like an omelette; but it’s not, it’s rice flour, turmeric gives it the yellow color, some people add coconut milk, and beer to the batter making the outer crepe shell crispy.  It’s a nicely light dish and can make a great appetizer. It’s often served with a heaping plate of fresh lettuce and herbs. You roll everything up in a big leafy bundle of lettuce and dip it into a sweet tangy fish sauce 😘 Then embrace the explosion of crunch and savory flavor in one bite, it’s so delicious! 🤤 

My verdict with this place, doesn’t compare to mom’s Banh Xeo. However, their version is still delightful but not the best I had 👌 It’s on the lighter side in flavor, maybe good for westerner to train their taste buds. 👅 #vietnamesefood #saigon

I’m very excited to be showing a ton of large photographs in a new solo show at @imogengallery in Astoria, Oregon opening today and running through March 4. The show is called “Far From Home” and is a meditation on my life at sea over many years while at work myself, and following the lives of other fishermen at work from Alaska to Europe. I’m honored to show this work alongside the #fisherpoets festival and the incredibly creative community of ocean dwelling misfits that the gathering has cultivated. If you haven’t been, you must experience the Fisherpoets festival Feb 23-25 and swing by the gallery!

Ben “Leyleği havada görmek” deyiminde de bahsedildiği gibi,  o yıl leylekleri havada gördüysem çok seyahat edeceğime inananlardanım. O sebeple de onlara farklı bir sevgim vardır. Biraz da bu yüzden yolumun ‘leyleklere yeni yuva’ projesiyle kesişmesinden ayrıca mutlu oldum. 

Adm Elektrik, Aydın Söke’de başlattığı ‘Leyleklere Yeni Yuva’ projesi ile doğal yaşamın sürdürülebilirliğine 14 yıldır destek oluyor. Elektrik direklerine özel platformlar kurarak leyleklere güvenli yuva alanları sağlamak, göç dönemlerinde yuvaları kontrol ederek zararlı maddeleri temizlemek ve elektrik hatlarını yalıtarak leyleklerin güvenliğini sağlamak gibi adımlar atarak, hem doğal dengeyi koruma hem de leyleklerin yaşam alanlarını güvence altına alma konusunda çok değerli bir rol üstlenmişler. 
Boyle  çevre dostu projeler, içimizi ısıtan bir umut ışığı gibi parlıyor. “Leyleklere Yeni Yuva” gibi projeler, yalnızca doğal yaşamı değil, dünyamızın daha yaşanabilir olacağına dair  umutları da besliyor 

Projeyi yerinde görebilmek için Söke’de çok güzel bir tarihi Rum köyü olan Doğanbey’i ve Ayşar Köyü’nü ziyaret ettik. Avşar Köyü’nde evine misafir olduğumuz Meryem Nine’nin kurtardığı Efe Leylek’le olan hikayesi ve doğa sevgisi yüreğimize bir başka dokundu. Bu  hikaye, insan ve doğa arasındaki özel bağın ne kadar değerli olduğunu bir kez daha hatırlatti. Bireysel çabaların yanında böyle projeler daha da çoğalsın 🙏🏻

La sala “el Molino” es hoy, un café-concierto y sala de fiestas. Pero su historia comienza en 1898, cuando el propietario de la tasca La Pajarera, un modesto barracón situado en la calle Vila Vilà esquina Rosal, harto de marineros borrachos y de albañiles escandalosos, vende su negocio por 100 pesetas.⠀⠀
·⠀⠀
·⠀⠀
El nuevo propietario, un andaluz llegado a Barcelona para hacer fortuna, le cambia el nombre por el de La Pajarera Catalana y monta un pequeño tablado. Al cabo de tres años ya ofrece una programación musical estable, restaurante a la carta e incluso un servicio gratuito de coches para facilitar el trayecto desde las Ramblas al local.⠀⠀

Pre & post menopause has been a rollercoaster! I’m 49, and I’ve been navigating this ride for the past 9 years. (Peri menopause started at age 40🫠)

One thing I forgot to mention in this video is that SLOW weight loss is the BEST kind of weight loss! There is no rush. Be consistent even if it takes years because the slower it comes off the better for long term success.

It’s taken me over 2 (maybe more) years to lose the belly fat. Before I get comments about how I looked great before and didn’t need to lose the weight… here’s the deal:

Visceral fat is fat around your organs & can lead to many health complications. When I started gaining weight around my belly, it wasn’t subcutaneous fat that you could pinch. It was hard, and felt so uncomfortable.

I knew that I had to figure out why this was happening or rather what I could do to stop & reverse the weight gain.

I’ve written several blogs about my discoveries from diet to exercise & exactly the changes I made so please check them out for more info.

I get messages from women every day about weight gain, specifically belly fat, & I’m posting this content for them.

When our hormones decline, we are at much greater health risks like heart disease, osteoporosis, and diabetes.

I recommend talking to your doctor & getting a full blood work up. Vitamin, mineral, & fiber deficiencies can make menopause even worse so it’s always good to know how well (nutrient-wise) you are eating.

With exercise, resistance based workouts to help build muscle will help protect your bones and increase your metabolism.

Consistency is hard for a lot of people. My only advice is to not make it a choice. 

Just like brushing your teeth, doing your laundry, or cleaning your dishes, you do it because it just has to get done.🙌🏻

“Unlike Earth, the atmosphere of Mars is dominated by micron-size dust aerosols, and the sky during sunset takes on a bluish glow.” From: Applied Optics Vol. 53, Issue 9

I’ve been experimenting with the public domain images available on the NASA website. What you see here are constructed entirely from that source. It’s been strange, and wasn’t until I found the article referenced above that I realized why. The light on Mars is ‘weird’ because the atmosphere is different. Go figure.

As I worked, the project became as much about understanding this unique light as playing with Martin landforms. The images here explore a few ways to bridge a blue light source - with golden/orange scattering, across a few different angles and times of day in a variety of atmospheric dust. It’s definitely not accurate, and surely exaggerated. (Check out the article, lots of math above my ability) The science was simply a point of departure for experimentation. The main gist i held in mind, is that blue can transition through purple & red or green & yellow to get to orange. Just walk your way around a color wheel. Fun. After a month tho, I’m ready to go look at some foliage.

The clam diggers. A rainy day conversation with, James Abbott McNeill Whistler, and Idris Khan, perhaps a drop in by Todd Hido...

I don’t know any of these cats. Idris and Todd are making powerful work today, but James was born in 1834, so it might be a challenge for us to get together. But, that’s the cool thing about art. We can dialogue with anyone throughout time.

This one finds me curious about their feelings on substance vs style. Inspiration vs appropriation. The relationship between how we make something, and why. 

Idris created a seminal series that appropriated the work of Bernd and Hilla Becher, with (it appears) the intent of adding meaning. Todd’s style is highly copied by other contemporary photographers, who arguably don’t add additional meaning. And James was a big proponent of art for aesthetics alone - meaning be damned (and fought over in lawsuits.) Of course his stance was taken in an age when images were relatively rare and filled with allegory, which to him might have made this fight feel - quite meaningful. 🙃
This was too good not to shoot something extra.

Eagle Pass, TX : A US Border Patrol agent holds a wailing child after helping several adolescent migrants - those already on US territory - cross large swaths of razor concertina wire set out by the TX National Guard. The wire is meant to dissuade and keep migrants from coming ashore and claiming asylum, a right enshrined in current American law.

#politics #immigration #migrants #eaglepasstx #migration

More hopeful migrants cross the Rio Grande River towards Eagle Pass, TX. All hoping for a better life and more opportunities in the US. But many face the harsh realities of an overloaded and broken American immigration system. Many apply for asylum before crossing, but often find themselves the victims of criminals, or the lack of adequate housing forces them into a desperate decision to cross into the US. 

#politics #immigration #eaglepasstx #photojournalism #reportage #migrants

Eagle Pass, TX - A migrant mother and daughter embrace after making it across the Rio Grande and past a riverbank lined with razor wire and TX National Guard. 
With all the political rhetoric these days - many forget these are actual human beings struggling to find a better life. 

#photojournalism #reportage #politics #eaglepass #migration #immigration

One of the other projects I did in Yemen were these portraits of Yemenis that played into the assignment I was working on, along with people I met during wanderings around different cities. 

This project could be the indirect reason I was detailed when I came back to the US. 

The second image is a portrait of the leader (at the time) of Al Qaeda’s political wing in Yemen.  He really liked the image and asked if I could send it to him. We used the old “bump” iPhone app to exchange the image. And I’m pretty sure my phone was compromised from there on out. 

To make matters worse - we were meeting in a large cafe for safety - the next interview subject came in to meet the writer and I a bit early. The third image is a portrait of the last Rabbi in Yemen. Obviously the head of Al Qaeda and the Rabbi kept their affiliations on the DL - so neither knew who each one was. They actually exchanged pleasant greetings and traded places - as the rabbi stayed for an interview and portrait.

The fourth image is a former Guantanamo prisoner who was returned to Yemen after serving a few years in the prison and found either not guilty or not worth US efforts to interrogate him. He was unemployed and trying to figure out how to continue a life cut short. 

#portrait #photojournalism #reportage #onassignment #documentary #yemen #tintype

A can’t -miss city to visit this Spring —@visitcarlsbad !

Recall some of our last visit highlights, and we have some recommendations for you if you are planning your Carlsbad trip for Spring.

1.The Flower Fields is opening on March 1st. If you like flowers and nature, @The_flower_fields is the place you don’t want to miss when in the area.

2.There are a couple hotels we stay in and really love.
a.@omnilacosta is a very beautiful hotel & also is a significant resort that it is a member of the Historic Hotels of America, part of the National Trust for Historic Preservation.
b.@Grandpacpal is a hotel right next to the Flower Fields, and you will have the whole flower field as your backyard when staying there — imagine that!
c.@legolandcalifornia hotel. — it’s heaven for a family with children, kids LOVE it! Parents, too! 😃

3.Places where we love to dine in Carlsbad:
a. @bobs_steakandchop house that is located in the @omnilacosta
b.@caserotacos — Best Mexican food we have tasted...our whole family agreed on this one!

4.There are also endless other activities offered in Carlsbad. I like my morning yoga in the flower fields, and my husband enjoyed his relaxing pool time, and my son can’t wait to go back for his @k1speed car racing with his friend. You can always find something fun to do there, and the weather will never disappoint you!

My journey through Tokyo… ✨🇯🇵 

Each moment becoming an unforgettable experience: 
1. Cerulean Tower Tokyu Hotel: A luxurious stay in Shibuya offering mesmerising cityscape views, transforming into a captivating tapestry of lights at night. 
2. Mount Mitake Mystical Forest: Just a short trip from Tokyo, Mount Mitake enchanted with mist-shrouded ancient cedars and the soothing sounds of nature. 
3. Mitake Sanso Shukubo Retreat: The traditional temple lodge provided an authentic escape, immersing in cultural heritage. 
4. KabukichoTheater: Stepping into Shinjuku’s Kabukicho Theater was a journey into Japan’s theatrical tradition, bridging the gap between modernity and history. 
5. Sunset over Mount Fuji unveiled a breathtaking sunset, casting a warm glow over the iconic silhouette of Mount Fuji. 
 #TokyoTokyo #Japan

Golden moments exploring Tokyo…✨
Amidst the vibrant city lights, there's a magical moment that unfolds as dawn breaks over Tokyo, watching the sunrise over the skyline from our Cerulean Tower Tokyu Hotel. On our last day we ventured to Kabukicho Theater, this vibrant district of Shinjuku is home to this iconic venue, where Kabuki performances adapted in modern styles unfold. Stepping into the theater is like stepping back in time, as the elaborate costumes, mesmerising makeup, and captivating storytelling transport you to the world of Japanese theater.
#tokyotokyo #tokyotokyooldmeetsnew #japan

Embrace the beauty of autumn in Tokyo with these unforgettable experiences: 

1. Mount Mitake: A hidden gem just over an hour from Tokyo, where ancient cedars and vibrant foliage paint the mountainside.
2. Hatonosu Valley Walk: Immerse yourself in nature's golden embrace with a stroll through the scenic  HatonosuHatanosu Valley. 
3. Lake Shiromaru Canoeing Experience: Glide through the serene waters, surrounded by the breathtaking colours of fall.
4. Mitake Sanso Shukubo Experience: Stay in a traditional temple lodge, experiencing the tranquility of Mount Mitake overnight. 
 
#TokyoTokyo #Japan

Just over an hour by train Mount Mitake is my favourite hidden gem and most surprisingly this is still part of Tokyo… ✨ As autumn paints the landscape, there's a particular magic that unfolds when you combine the vibrant colours of fall with the tranquil experience of canoeing on Lake Shiromaru. The turquoise blue and green of the lake reflects the kaleidoscope of autumn colours—shades of fiery red, golden yellow, and burnt orange. #TokyoTokyo #Japan #MountMitake

The glow from above…✨ As I reached the top of the enchanting Mount Mitake, the panoramic view of Mount Fuji unfolded before me. The sprawling metropolis of Tokyo lay in the distance, its iconic skyline blending with the horizon. Lush mountainside forests carpeted the landscape, their deep green and orange hues contrasting with the sleek architecture of Tokyo. #TokyoTokyo #Japan #MountMitake

Awaking to the beauty of Mount Mitake…✨🍁🇯🇵 A place where time slows down. Last autumn we embarked on an overnight adventure filled with lush mountainside forests and ancient spiritual sites where we experienced Japanese Shukubo, a traditional shrine lodging from the Edo Period. #TokyoTokyo #Japan #MountMitake #Tokyo

I have reclaimed my time and stopped pumping milk because of that I’ve been getting more sleep and things are easier the second time around. Um ponto que nos chamou atenção do @nalata.festival patrocinado por @tigerbeerbr, puro malte de Singapura que está nas ruas de SP, foi sua curadoria, assinada por Luan Cardoso @luancardoso que busca descobrir, olhar e valorizar novos artistas, e ficamos mais felizes ainda de ver a artista Daiane Lúcio @dai___dai___dai___ brilhando nesta edição do Festival. Nascida e crescida no interior de São Paulo, Daiane pinta uma jornada de redescoberta pessoal desde a pandemia. Conectando o Ser da infância até a vida adulta, tem a arte como maior ferramenta de cura interna, autoestima e protagonismo das próprias histórias. Vale muito a pena passar e conferir seu mural no endereço: Rua Padre Carvalho 780. #Publi • Aprecie com moderação.
#NalataFestival #TigerBeer #Arte #SaoPaulo #DaianeLucio #Mural

A @tigerbeerbr , puro malte de Singapura que está nas ruas de SP, foi uma das patrocinadoras do @nalata.festival que chega a sua quarta edição consolidado como um dos maiores festivais do país, um espaço de expressão artística e criatividade, onde grandes artistas de todo o mundo se unem para criar obras incríveis pela cidade de São Paulo. 
Agora que o Festival chegou ao fim, iremos fazer uma série de posts esta semana recordando e contando um pouco da história dos trabalhos que mais nos chamaram atenção este ano. 
Para começarmos, vamos falar do Artista Português @Vhils: suas obras são verdadeiramente uma forma de expressão emocional e social. Ele busca inspiração nas pessoas, nas cidades e nas histórias que elas têm a contar para a criação dos seus murais. Acredita que cada rachadura, cada marca e cada camada de tinta em uma parede conta uma história e é isso que ele quer revelar.Se você já teve a oportunidade de ver uma obra de Vhils em pessoa, sabe o impacto que ela pode ter. Se não, pode conferir no endereço: Av. Brigadeiro Faria Lima, ao lado do nº 822. #Publi • Aprecie com moderação.
#NalataFestival #TigerBeer #Arte #SaoPaulo #Vhils #Mural

—- Translate —-

@tigerbeerbr, pure malt from Singapore that is on the streets of SP, was one of the sponsors of @nalata.festival, which reaches its fourth edition, consolidated as one of the biggest festivals in the country, a space for artistic expression and creativity, where great artists from all over the world come together to create incredible works throughout the city of São Paulo.
Now that the Festival has come to an end, we will make a series of posts this week remembering and telling a little about the history of the works that caught our attention the most this year.
To start, let's talk about the Portuguese Artist @Vhils: his works are truly a form of emotional and social expression. He seeks inspiration from people, cities and the stories they have to tell when creating his murals. He believes that every crack, every mark and every layer of paint on a wall tells a story and that's what he wants to reveal. If you've ever had the opportunity to see a work by Vhils in person, you know the impact it can have.

A lo largo de estos años caminando junto al Señor, he comprendido la siguiente paradoja:
en ocasiones, 
planificamos en exceso y terminamos en posiciones nada agradables.
Por el contrario, 
cuando aceptamos que vamos en un barco sin timón y nos dejamos llevar por Dios, 
cada episodio del viaje contribuye al fortalecimiento de nuestro carácter, crecimiento indispensable para el cumplimiento de un propósito individual. 

En otras palabras, 
hacemos planes, pero todos nuestros planificaciones descansan en el Único Soberano, Dios. 

Este año fue de mucha bendición para mí, 
Dios me abrió las puertas del quirófano de una forma orgánica y me permitió documentar el gran trabajo de los profesionales de la salud. 

Llevo meses trabajando con el @Dr.Rodilla 
un médico que se convirtió  en un hermano y sembró  en mi, la curiosidad  de conocer a profundidad el arte de la medicina. 

En esta diosidad me di cuenta que, 
el sector salud de nuestro país está marginado en temas de redes sociales, 
son tantos los medios de comunicación seducidos por la polémica que tienen poco interés en documentar los logros, avances y loables hazañas de muchos médicos venezolanos.
Por este motivo, 
el colectivo de nuestro país, termina desinformado y repitiendo comentarios retrógrados muy alejados de la realidad. 

Este nicho desatendido me cautivó  profundamente por ende, tengo la intención  de quedarme y seguir compartiendo con ustedes el increíble trabajo de nuestros médicos. 

2024, con la ayuda de Jesús  estoy listo 🙏🏻 

Por el Señor son ordenados los pasos del hombre,
y el Señor  se deleita en su camino. Sal 37:23 

Dios bendiga tu vida en gran manera.

Hace cuatro días conocí a Leito (7 años).
En el pasado, logró tocar la campana que representa el sonido de victoria en la lucha contra el cáncer. 
Actualmente transita una recaída como paciente hematológico por Leucemia. 

La fundación Regalando Amor y Sonrisa liderada por Mónica Rondón, estableció comunicación directa con la familia Bera Motorcycles y juntos, coordinaron un agasajo para un grupo de pacientes hematológicos que visitaron el parque Salta el pasado 15 de febrero en conmemoración de la lucha contra el cáncer infantil, entre ellos, el Super Leito.
Leito, quería jugar en todos los espacios del parque, sinceramente estaba feliz, 
niños disfrutando el privilegio de ser niños. 

La cruda realidad se hizo presente cuando Leito dijo “Me siento mal”
las náuseas acompañadas de un fuerte mareo crearon una interferencia nerviosa en aquel momento de dicha. 
En ese instante, tuvimos que llorar pa’ adentro, Leito y yo hicimos ejercicios de respiración; 
el acompañamiento de los presentes sirvió para mitigar aquella visita nefasta que intentaba robarnos la paz. Gracias a Dios, el niño recuperó el aliento y pudo continuar el resto del día disfrutando con los demás. 

Cuando decidimos servir al prójimo siempre pagaremos un alto precio, nos encontraremos con escenarios sumamente punzantes, en ocasiones, la tristeza puede ser abrumadora, la inclemente realidad golpea más fuerte que un huracán, 
pero si tu intención está dirigida por la Voluntad de Dios, 
aprenderás a llorar pa’ adentro, 
tendrás la capacidad de gestionar tus emociones y negarte a ti mismo con el fin de sostener al prójimo 
¡Vale la pena pagar el precio, pero entiendo que no todos están dispuestos a pagarlo! 

Llorar pa’ adentro es un acto de amor que brindamos a quienes padecen etapas desérticas en sus vidas;

es centrar tu energía para sostener al que no tiene fuerzas;

es representar al Dios Omnipotente y proyectar su gloria a quienes son jamaqueados por un tiempo de adversidad. 

Si aun no sabes llorar pa’ adentro 
pídele a Dios que te enseñe.

¿Te sabes alguna canción?

llueva, truene o relampaguee ¡nos casamos!

El día de ayer se realizó la tercera edición de las bodas comunitarias en la plaza Altamira del municipio Chacao, 20 parejas se dieron el “si” en esta ceremonia auspiciada por el alcalde Gustavo Duque.

La gran mayoría de las parejas que decidieron casarse ya tienen una relación con una década de trayectoria aproximadamente, algunos asistieron en compañía de sus hijos y, 
en presencia de ellos, se intercambiaron los anillos. Este punto, me pareció digno de elogio.

En este tiempo, cuando el pacto matrimonial se encuentra en estado de desnutrición; 
ser testigo de 20 decisiones es una bendición.
Hablando de tiempo, 
la lluvia estuvo presente y puso a correr a las novias y todos los organizadores. Lo agradable de este fenómeno es un recordatorio del mismísimo Creador. 

En ocasiones, nuestras relaciones se asemejan a esos tiempos cálidos, agradables y tropicales
 ¡La época dorada! Pero la gran realidad,
el matrimonio se fortalece en los tiempos de tempestad, cuando la lluvia se impone y debemos fluir con las cosas que no podemos cambiar, aceptando que todo tiene su tiempo; 
tiempo de sol y tiempo de lluvia, 
lo importante es permanecer unidos, 
para ser ese cordón de tres dobleces junto a Dios.

Queridos matrimonios, 
¡Dios los bendiga en gran manera! Fue un honor para mi, ser testigo de sus pactos.

@gustavoduquesaez
@alcaldiadechacao

Tía Rubén y Tía Luisa, el verdadero amor.

Ambos tienen 73 años, 
nacieron el mismo día, mes y año.
Él de Maracaibo, ella de Maturín, 
en la actualidad tienen 53 años de casados.

Los primeros días de febrero visitamos la isla de Margarita y pudimos compartir con ellos, actualmente están viviendo allá. 

Tío Rubén, 
desde el año 2018 se encuentra dándole batalla a las secuelas de un ACV, 
tía Luisa, 
el pasado mes de octubre del 2023 sufrió una caída que generó una pequeña fractura en la rotula de su rodilla derecha, 
el origen de este accidente son unas frecuentes lagunas mentales que padece en la actualidad.

En mis años, he podido escuchar algunas declaraciones de amor, pero las de ellos traspasan el alma.

Tía Luisa dice de forma sentida, “me da pena cuando Rubén me pide algo y no recuerdo donde está”. 
Él responde, 
“tranquila mija, yo soy tu memoria”. 
El tío es un caballero con una historia fascinante, llena de afirmaciones que demuestran el valor de la palabra. 

El 09 de febrero, 
regresé a Margarita en compañía del @dr.rodilla para documentar unos casos en el Centro Medico El Valle. 
Hice una llamada a los tíos y dije:
“Tío, Dios mediante llego hoy con el Dr.  Bustillo,
¿puedes estar a las 11:00 am con tía Luisa en la clínica para ver cómo sigue la rodilla?”

El tío respondió con su característico cantado maracucho:
 “¡Machete mijo, a esa hora estoy por allá, sin ninguna novedad!”.

Llegamos a la clínica, media hora antes de lo pautado, sin embargo, ya tío Rubén y tía Luisa estaban ambos sentados en la entrada del consultorio. 

Todas las preguntas que realizó el Dr. Bustillo con relación a la rodilla de tía Luisa, fueron respondidas por tío Rubén, fechas exactas, tratamientos, fisioterapias, etc. 
Todo está almacenado en su memoria haciendo honor a esas palabras 
“Yo pensaré por los dos”. 
 
Tío Rubén aprendió es a escribir con la mano izquierda, debido a su limitante con la derecha, tiene un registro escrito detallado, 
ambos padecen de los achaques de la vejez, pero en su acompañamiento honran ese mandamiento de SER UNA SOLA CARNE. 

Mi respeto y admiración para ustedes, ustedes no necesitan hablar del amor porque SON el amor.

@dr.rodilla

Just over a year ago, I made the decision to part ways with my hair extensions, marking the beginning of a journey to restore the health of my hair. While my hair might have appeared thick and voluminous for years, the reality was quite different—brittle, challenging to maintain/grow, and on the thinner side.

I owe it to the professionals at @pierrehaddadhair for their guidance throughout this transformative process. Here are the key steps that played a role in bringing my hair to its current state:

- Adopting a Repairing Hair Care Routine using @perfecthair_guavahair keratin-infused shampoo, conditioner & mask
- Moderating the frequency of hair washing to once a week.
- Regular trims every four months for maintenance.
- Prioritizing scalp health with massages and oiling.
- Incorporating in-salon professional treatments for relaxation and rejuvenation.
- Reducing the use of heat styling tools.
- Investing in a silk pillow for added care and comfort. #HairRevivalJourney #GratefulForExperts

The Castillo family attends the Annual Día de los Muertos Art and Music Festival in Whittier, California. Veronica, as Mexico’s cultural icon La Calavera Catrina, stands with her two boys, Aiden and Samson, who are dressed as characters from the film “Nacho Libre.“

Celebrated all over the world, Día de los Muertos (the Day of the Dead) is a Mexican holiday in which people remember their ancestors. Many build altars, or ofrendas, to honor them, and ply them with items such as the deceased person’s favorite food. La Calavera Catrina originated from an etching by Mexican illustrator José Guadalupe Posada in the early 20th century. The etching satirizes the country’s elite just before the Mexican revolution. La Catrina is a popular costume tied to El Día de los Muertos and central to Mexican identity.

This portrait was made on assignment for National Geographic in 2017, with @kchete77, while working on the story “How Latinos Are Shaping America’s Future.”

El Camino Real de Baja California runs from Tijuana to Loreto, Mexico. Many are familiar with El Camino Real of Alta California (modern-day California), which is lined with bells and passes through cities like Los Angeles and San Francisco. The old road in Baja has been forgotten, even though it played a massive role in the development of the whole region. The roads were originally trails made by the indigenous communities of the region, whose people were killed, died from diseases and were used as slave labor to build the road by the Spanish.
 
 
-Felipe Villa Poblano, who has lived next to the Mission Santa Gertrudis for 26 years, has a small store and looks after the mission. Mission Santa Gertrudis was established in 1751 by the Jesuits to convert Cochimí Indians.
 
- A dirt road heads down to a valley near San Pedro Mártir Park near the ruins of Mission San Pedro Mártir. The Mission of San Pedro Mártir was established in 1794 by the Dominicans in an attempt to control the Kiliwa Indians.
 
- Mother Mary stands in a side room of the Mission San Ignacio, which was founded in 1728 by the Jesuits.
 
To see more from this project by @kchete77 and @ivankphoto please visit @ruta_camino_real /  @runa_photos, @panospictures

Exploring beautiful Cuba 😍 Here is a rough guide to our Itinerary 👇🏻

🇨🇺 Havana, we spent a couple of days exploring the beautiful city of Havana where we ate at well known restaurants such as La Bodeguita Del Medio, had drinks on the rooftop of the Kempinski Hotel overlooking the Capitol and the Great Theatre of Havana, watched the famous Tropicana Show which has been going since 1939, walked the streets until our feet hurt and took a ride in a hot pink convertible classic car! 🚗 

🇨🇺 Santiago De Cuba, a 1 hour flight from Havana. We spent a few days exploring the bustling town of Santiago de Cuba and nearby places such as La Gran Piedra, the Cobre Basilica and El Morro castle before going on a bus ride to Baracoa stopping off at the most Wastern point in Cuba called Maisi ⛪️ 

🇨🇺 Baracoa, the oldest city and one of the most charming in Cuba. Located in the Guantanamo province, this Cuban jewel is hidden among mountain ranges and beautiful beaches. We visited black beaches, chocolate farms and cruised down the river in Yumuri Canyon 🚣‍♂️

One very bumpy bus ride later we arrived at the gorgeous…

🇨🇺 Cayo Saetia, here we spent the day swimming, eating, riding horses and relaxing in the stunning nature and the most turquoise sea. We then had a sunset cruise on a catamaran towards Holguin with lots of music and drinks 🍹 

All in all such a memorable and eye opening trip. Learnt a lot, met some great people and made memories for life! ❤️

#havana #cuba

Here are some tips for budget friendly trips:

✈️ *Avoid Peak Season* Not only a way to avoid crowds but you’ll usually be able to get a better deal. You might not be able to guarantee nice weather, but your destination will at least be a lot less crowded!

✈️ *Book in Advance* Prices will often go up as time gets closer to your trip. Booking train journeys, accommodation & flights ahead of time guarantees you won’t get stung by a last minute expensive prices.

✈️ *Purchase travel insurance* It may seem like an additional upfront expense, but it’s best to view it as an investment that can help you save money during medical emergencies and unexpected cancellations.

✈️ *Using public transportation* during your trip can save you money. The bus or whatever the local transport of the country you’re visiting is always cheaper than a taxi or an Uber. Walking is my personal favourite way to discover anywhere! 

✈️ *Choose cheaper accommodation* Hotels can be quite expensive so choose a more budget friendly stay such as a hostel or apartment. 

✈️ *Pack light* to avoid baggage expenses. Airports impose pretty hefty extra fees for large and heavy baggage. Also pack well, write lists (I have a notes app full of them😄) so you don’t forget anything and have to buy duplicate things abroad that you already have at home. 

✈️ *Eat Local* Stay away from the touristy areas. You can often see places that are popular with the locals, they serve cheaper food and you’ll get a much more authentic look into the cuisine of that country!

✈️ *Save up frequent flyer miles* It’s definitely worth joining a frequent flyer program & racking up those miles/points. Over time they really add up and can get you discounted flights and upgrades!

✈️ *Bring your own food* Whenever possible, stock up on sandwiches and snacks for the trip. Avoid buying meals at the airport/on the road/hotel minibar which are £££.

✈️ *Skip overpriced Tours* Explore yourself, with the information available online, it’s simple and easy to conduct your own tour for free rather than paying for a guide.

..and if you spend less on one adventure, you have money to spend on another! 🥳

Snippets from our cosy stay at South Lodge hotel in Horsham. 🏡 Boasting beautiful views across the South Downs, South Lodge is a five-star quintessential country house hotel tucked away in the West Sussex countryside. Located only 1.5 hours from London, South Lodge is the perfect escape from the hustle and bustle of daily life. We spent 2 days there relaxing, enjoying the spa, delicious food & the peace and quiet. 🌿

🛌 Our room, Elizabeth La Bay, was stunning, spacious and modern with a big bed and sprawling views over the grounds (and the downs) 🌳 A fun fact about our room is during the war Sir Winston Churchill stayed at South Lodge on occasion. A lift was believed to have taken him directly up to his favoured room, the ‘Elizabeth Le Bay room’ 

🧖‍♀️ The spa is amazing with a swimming pool, sauna, marble salt room, aromatic steam room, ice bucket shower and a stage of the art gym. Outside you’ll find a heated hydrotherapy infinity pool, plus a wild swimming pond which I spent over 30 minutes splashing around amongst the reeds before warming up with a delicious supper in Botanic, the spa’s Mediterranean influenced restaurant. 

Our stay short but sweet and we felt throughly rested when we left and I would highly recommend a visit to South Lodge. ♥️

If you’re NEW to my page, here’s a brief professional history of me 😳

👦🏻 Firstly, I certainly wasn’t always an athlete or any kind of “model”. I was a pretty chunky teenager! An only child in a single-parent family that probably needed a bit more attention…

📚 Before I qualified as a PT (way back in 2010) I was a full time residential Architect and also a part time club DJ. Funny combo right?

📝 My first PT job was at LA Fitness in my hometown of Cheltenham (U.K.) 13 years ago 😮 I was SO excited. I used to walk around with a clipboard (no iPad) and a stopwatch around my neck!

💪🏽 I’d already been devoted to bodybuilding for many years before I became a PT, but this career move REALLY kicked me into obsession. I won @miami.pro & went to compete as a WBFF Pro and win money for prancing around in #Vegas!

💰As time went on my profile increased & I was one of the lucky athletes that had an actual paid sponsorship. I was lead athlete @scimx for 4 years. Taken to expos, I did countless interviews and started to build a massive following.

👨‍🏫 In 2015 I started mentoring other trainers and became the PT manager at @gymboxofficial in London - nurturing all the new graduates how to run their PT business.

📷 In 2018 I achieved a lifelong dream of making the Muscle & Fitness cover. I had read and adored the magazine since I was 18!!

👴🏻 After this I decided to “retire” from the physique obsession and competing. I’d had an amazing few years but I knew it wasn’t exactly “healthy” 💊 and I wanted to focus more on my Coaching. This was tough!

🚴🏼‍♂️ Moving away from bodybuilding came with a slight personal identity crisis…..and I needed something else to distract me so I started doing Road Cycling (and still do!) When you try riding a bike uphill fast with ACTUAL fit people, and your ego gets ground to dust 💀

🇳🇿 Fast forward to 2022 and I decide with @miki_ferris that London life was way too busy, & transient and we fancied a diffrerent lifestyle. So we shipped our lives over to New Zealand! Now we get more fresh air and sunshine!

Scotland Fix of the Day: There are days in Scotland where I relish nothing so wonderful but the fresh breeze on an island shore, rain racing away to reveal a bright landscape, or the melancholy of clouds gathering at sunset. Right now, in the depth of winter, it might be worth thinking forward to such times coming again – and hatching a plan to be there when they do. 

Island locations: 
1. Berneray in the Outer Hebrides
2. Westray in Orkney
3. Fair Isle
4. Isle of Lewis
5. Isle of Harris

Scotland Fix of the Day: Scottish landscapes loom large in my photographic world so I'm very pleased to share that The Independent Photographer has a new profile about me that shines quite a bit of light into my photography and background. All credit to Josh Bright for pulling it together so brilliantly. (He's more generous than I deserve but I'm not arguing.) Most of all I appreciate the chance to talk about why landscapes are so important to me, why they speak not just to geography but also to our hearts and souls. I'll also be judging their 2023 landscape awards so it's an added chance to connect with beloved places and photography. 

You can find a link in to the Independent Photographer article in my bio.

Looking for Scotland: If Scotland is on your travel list for 2024 let me offer my Top Ten Things To Do. Everybody has their list of Best Castles and Must See sites. With my list I hope to suggest ways of seeing Scotland that might get you away from checklist travel and into another realm. Here goes:

1. Visit a castle (of course) but let the history wash over you. Do a deep dive into its turns of fortune, failures and disasters. Eilean Donan is a good one. 
2. Find a Highland Games in some remote glen. Take part in the gathering, however you can. If they have a visitors tug of war, pull for all your worth. If they have a dance, dance.
3. Find a remote country house hotel that knows Scottish hospitality. Let them spoil you for a couple of days. I’d hole up in Eilean Iarmain on Skye.
4. Sit amongst the puffins. Be patient.
5. Find someplace with stonking, bloody Scottish history. Iona is just one of many, but it’s got Celtic Saints, Viking raids and Macbeth in the graveyard.
6. Visit a coastal village with one pub. Buy somebody a pint. Pennan is a likely choice, but watch Local Hero before you go. 
7. Be picky about which distillery you visit. Avoid glitz. Strathisla is one of those ancient distilleries that still looks old…because it actually is. 
8. Lie down in the heather and take a nap.
9. Find a red phone booth that is still working and call someone. 
10. Spend an evening at a stone circle in the moonlight. The Stones of Stenness in Orkney is a good bet. 

There’s more, of course, and much I have yet to see myself. Before you go buy Scotland, the Best by Peter Irvine, the hands down best Scottish guide book. Relish its handpicked lists of treasures and oddities long before you go. 

#scotland #scotlandtravel #hebrides #orkney #highlands #scottishhighlands

Scotland Fix: Few settings seem so right for listening to the Great Highland Bagpipe as a rainy day at the head of Loch Shiel. Here at the Glennfinnan Gathering the piping competition takes place down by the shore, the very place where Bonnie Prince Charlie came ashore on his ill-fated Jacobite mission. The bagpiper is concentrating as he plays the piobaireachd, the ancient classical music set down in the mists of lost history and still revered today. He paces around the platform, "slowly, but not too slowly" in precise, measured steps. The judge stares into the distance, careful to not let the magnificent, romantic scene cloud his judgement. Judge and piper share a quest to keep alive something that could die without them. For a bagpiper, I think, this is Carnegie Hall.

Scotland Fix of the Day: Scottish landscapes — like the Hairy Loch on the Isle of Skye — have a special drama to them, something that goes beyond the mere picturesque, something that goes to the soul of an ancient land. But telling their story is never as simple as just getting a dramatic landscape corralled inside a camera frame. And it’s always possible that showing less tells a more interesting story than showing more. My practice is to try every compositional option that I can while the light lasts.  I can decide later what worked best. 

By the way, the Hairy Loch has its share of legends attached, some quite morbid. Do these tales add color for you, or put you off?

Scotland Fix of the Day: Scottish landscapes — like this view of Uig Bay on the Isle of Lewis — have a special drama to them, something that goes beyond the mere picturesque, something that goes to the soul of an ancient land.  This stunning bay empties completely twice a day at low tide — it’s that shallow. Vikings favored it on their journeys into the Hebrides and onward to Ireland. That wee graveyard has a great ghost story, too. 

Would you walk across at low tide?  Comment?

Scottish landscapes reveal much of Scottish character, especially out in the islands where the Atlantic storms do battle with the land. So it was that a sodden pony on North Uist taught me a lesson on rainy day. 

It sidled up next to my car, refusing to go stand a ways off in the moor to make a pretty picture for me, a picture that did not involve a soggy mane. But then it dawned on me: the soggy mane was the picture, a pattern of ringlets redolent of Celtic symbols seen here a thousand years ago. 

Sometimes I’m afraid that the land is trying to tell me something and I won’t get it. Over fifty years of photography that has happened to me plenty of times. It’s daunting to think that you can be standing in front of something wonderful, and just not be able to see it. So I thank this pony for its patience. It stood there long enough for me to get it. 

Had any stories of revelations that got away?  Comments welcome.

In Scotland the right light can produce magic on the landscape. Such was the case when Loch Cill Chriosd lit up with the first rays of sunrise that morning as I was driving back from Elgol on the Isle of Skye. 

By the way, locals call it the Hairy Loch for good reason owing to these grasses. It’s often calm and a prime photo stop on the Isle of Skye — if the midgies are held at bay. 

Lots of legends attached to this place, that St. Columba drove away an evil spirit in 570 AD (he did that a lot), that a shape shifting water horse (Kelpie) took up residence and in the form of a handsome young man lured maidens to their death in the loch, even that a Norwegian princess named Saucy Mary is buried on top of Beinn na Caillich back there. 

Got a favorite Isle of Skye moment?  Comment below.

Scotland Fix of the Day: Getting away sometimes leads to finding yourself. That’s one attraction of the Scottish landscape for me, the chance to truly be alone with the place, unfettered with expectations, content to accept the character of the land (and of yourself) as it is. Here are a few places that have evoked that sense for me. 

1. The long one-track road on Jura that ends after 17 miles just south of the house where George Orwell wrote 1984.
2. Eilean na Moine, the wee island in Loch Eilt that became most known as the site of Dumbledore’s grave. Few other island seem to stand so alone. 
3. The moors of Assynt stretch off into vast openness when seen from atop Sgorr Tuath, or from Stac Pollaidh across the way. 
4. Evening at the Ring of Brodgar in Orkney can be sublime, the stones — and endless time — your only companions. I’ve often felt comforted here. 

Are you one of the travelers who seek out such solitude, even loneliness, in the landscape. 

For more Scotland follow the link in my bio. While you are there browse my other work for National Geographic.

Scotland Fix of the Day: Over the Sea to Skye is a beautiful song and an alluring thought.  One such journey is from Elgol over to Loch Coruisk where you are surrounded by the jagged sweep of the Black Cuillins wrapping around the remnants of the ancient caldera.  My favorite boat that makes this trip is the Bella Jane, the journey over as rewarding as the hike once you get there. On the way back the River Scavaig tumbles down to the sea, the shortest river in the British Isles. Been there? Did you see the Kelpie?

A Saturday morning stroll! The lovely @claudiamariaca walks the starkly beautiful Paracas Desert. We’ve worked together a couple of times, in Peru and in Vegas. Always amazing in front of the lens. Nikon D810 with a 70-200mm lens, from a fashion project a few years ago. The beauty and benefit of one big light source! @profoto B1-X through a 4’ RFI Octa, fitted with a fabric grid. The grid helps keep light splash off the road in the foreground of the picture, which is always a dead bang giveaway as to where you put the light. Big light even from a distance is wonderful. Telephoto gives the endless road compression and a shape. And Claudia conveys to the scene a casual, nonchalant elegance.
As in “I always walk on abandoned desert roads in an evening gown, doesn’t everyone?” I believe the French give it the term insouciance. 😀

#saturday #picoftheday @NikonUSA  #NikonPro #NikonAmbassador #NikonD810 #claudiamariaca

Nature abounds. Just back from another trip to the Amazon Rainforest in Ecuador, a truly astonishing place to photograph. Our group had the benefit and wonder of staying at LaSelva Lodge, a jewel of an ecolodge nestled in the heart of the jungle. Perched on a lagoon, the wild nature of the jungle is literally at your doorstep every day. Beautiful rooms, wonderful food, and an array of incredibly knowledgeable guides who lead you through a week of discovery with certainty and expertise. A terrific week. Thanks to all in our group, hardy travelers all, who made lovely images. The pic of this squirrel monkey was made with the @nikonusa Z 9 with the 180-600 f/6.3, ISO 6400 at the edge of dusk, hand-held from a canoe. Shutter speed was at 1/640th.  The new construction of Nikon’s long glass tremendously aids in hand holding, especially from an unstable platform. Many thanks to @fancygirlstreetboy and @ari_espay for putting together an amazing trip, as always. And to  @tamaralackey for her wonderful teaching and friendship.

The lavender fields in the south of France are stunningly beautiful and arrayed, wonderfully, as if the farmers had photographers in mind. Beautifully linear, graphic rows of astonishing color greet the eye. Designed equally well for long or wide glass. In this instance, shot with the Nikkor 200-500mm on a Nikon D850, the compression of the long glass makes the fields seem endless, which, in reality, they pretty much are. Gorgeous sunlight graced us on this particular morning. We were shooting commercially, so we had obtained permission for the field, paid a fee, signed a property release. Our lovely young model was the daughter of our location producer, also a wonderful occurrence. But…the best part ☕️🥮! We had on location catering for the crew. French bread and croissants, coffee, fruit, etc. Great memory out there in the fields of France. 

#saturdaymorning #portraitphotography #nikonambassador #nikonnofilter @nikonusa #lavenderfields

Hoping to make a splash in 24? 😀Nate Newton, then of the Dallas Cowboys, certainly did. Shot on medium format film for Sports Illustrated in the 90’s, for a story concentrating on offensive lineman, who are the biggest guys on the field. Newton was part of the legendary “Wall of Dallas” a famed front line. He was also pretty well known for his girth, tipping the scales at maybe, like, 330 or so. Which I did not take into account on the first of these diving board leaps as I was balancing a Mamiya RZ67 Pro with a motor drive and a 50mm lens on a little float type thing, such as one would get at Walmart. Designed for a kid, not the pool based tidal wave Nate caused when he hit the water. Major water over the camera and me. Luckily, I had a second camera, and as I remember we put the soaked camera down on the deck, in the Dallas August sun, and that revived it. Thankfully it wasn’t fully dunked! But we went back to work, got this and some other images. Nate was great to work with.

#wednesdaywisdom #waybackwednesday #picoftheday #filmphotography

Looking to 24! And fitness is on a lot of folk’s minds as New Year’s resolutions abound. One of the most amazing, talented and supremely fit people I ever photographed was Gabby Reece. Pro volleyball player of legendary status, fitness coach, model, author, podcaster. Shot this back in film days, medium format. The notion of strength I tried to conjure by having a huge prop volleyball made and to have her support it, Atlas-like. We got the ball to the desert and inflated it, and it was way too shiny and new. So the crew pretty much chipped in a bunch of our water to make a mud puddle on the parched turf and we then rolled the ball around in it. Location improv! Another significant improvisation was to take two hi-rollers off to the side and run hi strength monofilament fishing line to little loops that had been built into the prop ball. Barely visible even in the original negatives. Never published this frame before, always went with the color, but the B&W I think actually accentuates Gabby’s strength. LMK what you think. Highly recommend her podcast BTW. Also, she is married to monster wave surfer Laird Hamilton who is legendary himself. Together they are a font of fitness and excellence wisdom. 

#saturdaymorning #picoftheday #athlete #fitnessgoals #monochrome

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar

On 14 October 1492, Christopher Columbus touched land after leaving Spain on the islands known as Guanahaní, today called the Bahamas. Taking slaves (he was a slave owner, too), two months later, on 5 December, he landed on the island of Taino. In a typical conquering manner, renaming it La Isla Española, or The Spanish Island, later called Hispaniola. Today, Hispaniola is divided—the Dominican Republic on the east and Haiti on the west.

Knowing the culture of the Caribbean well, for the @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar (read the first sugar caption in my IG), Haiti is unique…in Haitian Vodou, sugar is of spiritual importance.

Vodou came with slaves forced from central and western Africa to Haiti shortly after Columbus. This most special, beautifully unique form of spirituality is often misunderstood and interwoven in Haitian culture.

@RegineParicia, a specialist in Haitian culture, knew of a Rada lwa ceremony 30 km (about 20 mi) from Port-au-Prince. Traveling with filmmaker @AnkaVision (Anka was creating a NatGeo TV Amazing Photos documentary for this chapter on sugar), we were welcomed by the community of Dumilseau Village in La Plaine into rituals, healings, and trance like nowhere else on earth.

Why sugar and vodou?

Sugar is essential in Haitian Vodou–many spirits require sweet, sugary substances.

Intricate patterns of religious symbols, called Veve’s, are created on the earth using flour, ground coffee, and offerings of sugar…sodas, and Barbancourt rum, made from sugarcane.

A table-like altar was created for the Cra Bi Nay Ceremony to honor the spirit Bossou, adorned with orange sodas, Coca-Cola, and candies.

Before a cow was sacrificed, many went into a trance, pouring sugary rum over their bodies and making offerings of sugar to the spirits. Others were healed with soda. Music was hypnotic, a reminder of the rhythms I heard as a child living in the Bahamas playing with my classmates at their homes, some of whom were of Haitian descent.

A short film in this album shares this beautiful intensity where sugar and spirituality merge.

@NatGeo #haiti #vodou #sugar #spirituality #CultureOfSugar #ForgottenStory

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.

The history of sugar is bitter by dark moments of our human ego and desires for control.

For thousands of years, this sweetness was cultivated from the grass known as sugarcane, moving from Oceania by trade.

In colder climates of Europe where sugarcane would not grow, the demand for sugar during a time when such delights were rare, and spreading Colonization, the spice wars began in the 15th century for flavor-filled items like nutmeg, cinnamon, and yes, sugar. By the 18th century, most sugar was obtained from the West Indies.

During the Napoleonic Wars, sugar supplies were cut off by the English blockade of continental Europe.

To make up for this loss, Napoleon Bonaparte encouraged the growing of beets…in the 17th century, a German chemist discovered white and red beetroot contained sucrose, able to extract sugar.

After gaining a presence in France, the introduction of sugar beet production in the United States was first established, a short drive from where I live to North Hampton, MA—by 1883, ceasing operation.

It wasn’t until seeds arrived in North Dakota from Michigan in the late 1800s that sugar from beets became viable. With heavy labor done by German and Russian immigrants who moved to North Dakota for jobs, the surrounding areas of Fargo became the epicenter of sugar production in the United States.

In 1899, American Crystal Sugar was founded, and so began the most significant crop production of sugar beets in North America, along the Red River Valley in North Dakota.

From the @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar, which was never published (read why in the caption in my first post of this story), sharing with you the mesmerizing movement of how nearly all white processed sugar at American Crystal Sugar is produced for US consumption.

To understand the enormity of our desire for sweetness, the images inside the storage silo represent 35 million tonnes, or the equivalent of 7 million 2.3 kg (5 lb) bags of sugar.

A short film is in this album on the mysterious machines that create this sugar desire.

@NatGeo ##UnitedStates #NorthDakota #SugarBeets #sugar #CultureOfSugar #ForgottenStory

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.

Once a rare spice, every genus of sugar originates east of the Wallace Line in Papua New Guinea.

Beginning in around 4 C.E., sugar moved from Oceania through trade often connected to conflict and slavery…at that time in history, nowhere else on earth had or grew sugar.

For the unpublished @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar, these crystals are culturally unimaginable in PNG culture.

Unaware of what to expect, my contact was Father Paul Kanda, a Papuan Catholic priest who told me, “John, just come, I will show you.”

After four days of travel by propeller plane and trucks to reach the highlands of Enga Province, there was a wedding.

Father Kanda drove us to a hillside where I met William Waikenda, a kamongo or tribal leader, preparing for the Yari ceremony in Wapai Village. He would lead the Yole Maingi (bride prize) ceremony in a few hours, uniting a woman and man before a Christian marriage.

Insects swarmed everywhere, drawn to the sweetness of sugarcane leaning against a tree.

Down the hill, I found the groom, 24-year-old Samuel Tembe, skipping along a pathway through a gorgeous landscape of greenness to meet his bride.

At a clearing in Wapai was 20-year-old Janet Sani and her family; Samuel took his place next to his future wife and immediately began the Yole Maingi (bride prize).

Why sugar?

Giving and eating raw sugarcane is essential; the bridge or conduit to unite two tribes creates harmony between the bride and groom’s tribes. A practice for thousands of years in the Highlands of Papua New Guinea.

When leaving, William Waikenda insisted I take three sugarcane sticks. Unkind to say no, confused about what to do with this long gift, I rested three canes out of the truck window, enjoying a few bites. Later, I gave Father Kanda the rest of the massive poles.

Sharing more stories of the fascination with sugar from Papua New Guinea in the coming days…. The Yole Maingi ceremony only touches the unimaginable sugar culture, the roots of this now common sweetener.

Also included is a short video.

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
A story that never was published due to changing writers (read the caption in the first photograph in this series, Forgotten Story); for more than a year, I created an essay for @NatGeo about how this common sweet substance has a captivating, often lengthy, dark global history.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
With India having the unpleasant recognition as the second highest rate of diabetes (China is first, both due to large populations) and wanting to return to my favorite spiritual city, Varanasi (Banaras, also known as Kashi), I did the usual movement of learning, while not knowing or expecting anything. Wandering the streets and alleys, getting lost.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This was when I met Ram Ji, squatting like a guru upon a small wooden stool along Godowlia Street, cleaning teeth, making dentures, and catering to the dental needs of the poorest of the poor. He didn’t know his age, guessing at the time he was 85. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Known as Baba ji to his clients, he learned dentistry from his father and, since childhood, had been a roadside dentist, training more than 30 street dentists, including his son.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Spending three days together with a nonstop flow of customers, Ram ji attributed his busy practice to the high consumption of sugar, which is abundant in nearly all Indian foods, especially chai.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In all the noise, dirt, and chaos on Godowlia Street, Ram ji miraculously kept his dental tools clean, though his finger hygiene was a bit questionable...there is a short video at the end of this story. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Returning to Banaras a few years ago to give him equipment donated by dental friends, I learned from his son that Baba ji had passed away. A kindest man who gave so much to others, often for free.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
@NatGeo #india #varanasi #banaras #kashi #sugar #dentist #StreetDentist #CultureOfSugar #ForgottenStory

Forgotten Story: Going through the archive for an exhibition opening later this year in Tbilisi, I remembered a story that never was published in @NatGeo: The Culture of Sugar.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
For over a year, I explored how this common sweet substance has a captivating, often lengthy, dark history.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Why did the sugar story not publish?
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
National Geographic had commissioned a new writer. Midway through the reporting, they rejected the manuscript. Such unfortunateness was a gift…I could write the visual narrative, unconstrained in complete curiosity.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Around midway through, I was introduced to a new writer, sharing what I had been creating. After a few months, this writer’s manuscript was also rejected.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
When the photography was completed — Oceania, South and Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, and the United States — the magazine commissioned a third writer, Rich Cohen, author of Sweet and Low: A Family Story, a memoir about the creation of the artificial sweetener in the pink packet invented by Benjamin Eisenstadt, Cohen’s grandfather.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
National Geographic accepted Rich’s manuscript, but this time, the text had nothing to do with the culture of sugar: the story focused more on the health issues of sugar, not a global narrative on the culture of sugar.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My good friend, @robertclarkphoto, was hired to photograph sugary foods in his studio, creating beautiful images to accompany Cohen’s text.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I was not upset at this unexpectedness. Life often shifts.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Will begin publishing this story here on the discovery of a forgotten photo essay on sugar.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Oh, here’s a touching to come…Christopher Columbus didn’t travel from Spain to discover an alleged “new world.” (there were millions of fellow humans already there!).
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
He came to the western hemisphere looking for new places to cultivate sugar, a grass family species originating in Papua New Guinea.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Today is the 11th year of Paul Salopek’s walk around our world, the @outofedenwalk. Paul began this unimaginable journey on January 10, 2013, from Herto Buri, Ethiopia, returning to that day with walking partner Ahmed Elema in the Afar desert. I have learned so much and been inspired by Paul for over a decade. Walking together across two continents and 12 countries on this 24,000-mile odyssey, following in the footsteps of our ancestors on this @NatGeo project. Last year, I met up with Paul in northern China as we neared Beijing (that story will be published in National Geographic later this year). A few million more footprints to go, sending kindness, the fire of doing to my friend Paul and his many more million footprints to come as we walk towards North America, onward over the coming years through Central and South America, till reaching the tip of Argentina in Tierra del Fuego. Love you, Paul, seeing you soon…❤️✨

No words can explain the uniqueness. An event of photography like I never before have hosted.

From 27 February through 13 March 2024, we return to my second home, Bali, for the most unimaginable storytelling workshop. 16 days on the Island of The Spirits during sacred events of Galungan, Kuningan, Melasti, and the profound day of Nyepi ~ the Day of Silence.

It has been decades since these most important days occurred so close to one another, each expressing profound moments during the most extended workshop I’ve ever hosted.

This intimate gathering will stretch your consciousness through awareness of long-form visual storytelling. Guide only ten photographers on creating an in-depth essay, like I create for National Geographic. In deepest giving to your narrative, your completed project should be ready for pitching to a magazine, even becoming a book or exhibition.

Only two spaces remain until we are full.

As always, we are offering a special workshop fee for early registration and even more discounts for those returning from our Workshop Family.

Complete details about this unimaginable event are at the link in my Instagram bio or by visiting stanmeyer.com

I suggest registering as soon as possible, as these two last spaces will fill quickly.

In early 2024, I look forward to lifting you through the meditation of long narrative visual storytelling during this unfathomably unique period of Indonesian culture in Bali.

John

I’ve always followed the traditional thinking, honed into me by #NatGeo, that a photo should be as realistic as possible, without major edits or removing unwanted objects. For journalism, that works, but it leaves little room for more extreme artistic expression in post production. It’s taken me a long time to free my mind enough to explore that other side, which seems strange to me now as I write that because I consider myself a pretty creative and out of the box thinker. I guess that I’ve been so focused on the perfect/real photo that I never let myself think about what a photo could be if I completely break free of those chains. So I’ve been playing around with more extreme photoshop editing on a couple of images to see where it takes me, and it’s been really fun and freeing. I’d never call these real photos, but they are based on actual images I’ve taken (I’ve included both the edited and unedited images in two examples). What do you think of the heavily edited surreal photos? Too much? Or shall I continue down this path?
Lone twiga (giraffe) ambling at sunset on the great open expanse of Kenya’s Maasai Mara. #kenya #safari

Eye to Eye. 

It’s tough to watch any animal die. Our human instinct is to look away and feel a sense of shame/guilt for even wanting the hunt to happen in the first place. It’s a normal and perfectly fine reaction. But life in the Maasai Mara is not easy, and lions must kill to survive. We’ve lost over 90% of the lion population in the last 50+ years. Lions are in serious trouble, and I can’t imagine a world in which we can’t see them in the wild. So I try to bear witness, without wishing a kill to happen but also not looking away when it does.

On this particular morning, these two male lions ambushed a rather large herd of buffalo, and managed to separate this one from the group. It was over rather quickly, as these two brothers are expert hunters and together there’s not much that they can’t take down. That’s more than I can say for other kills I’ve witnessed. 

Such is the tug and pull (figuratively, and in this case, quite literally too) of life on the Mara. #kenya #safari
